{{flu}}
The '''2009 flu pandemic''' or '''swine flu''' was an [[influenza pandemic]], and the second of the two pandemics involving [[influenza A virus subtype H1N1|H1N1 influenza virus]] (the first of them was the [[1918 flu pandemic]]), albeit in a new version. First described in April 2009, the virus appeared to be a new strain of H1N1 which resulted when a previous triple [[reassortment]] of bird, swine and human flu viruses further combined with a Eurasian pig flu virus,<ref>{{Cite journal|date=9 July 2009|title=Geographic Dependence, Surveillance, and Origins of the 2009 Influenza A (H1N1) Virus|journal=[[New England Journal of Medicine]]|volume=361|issue=2|pages=115–119 |pmid=19474418 |url=http://content.nejm.org/cgi/content/full/NEJMp0904572 |accessdate=14 May 2010|first1=Vladimir |last1=Trifonov |first2=Hossein |last2=Khiabanian |first3=Raul |last3=Rabadan|doi=10.1056/NEJMp0904572}}</ref> leading to the term "[[swine flu]]" to be used for this pandemic.<ref>{{Cite news|author=From Caleb Hellerman [[CNN]] |url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/HEALTH/06/11/swine.flu.who/ |title=Swine flu 'not stoppable,' World Health Organization says |publisher=CNN |date=11 June 2009 |accessdate=3 April 2010}}</ref> Unlike most strains of influenza, H1N1 does not disproportionately infect adults older than 60 years; this was an unusual and characteristic feature of the H1N1 [[pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Writing Committee of the WHO Consultation on Clinical Aspects of Pandemic (H1N1) 2009 Influenza|year=2010|title=Clinical Aspects of Pandemic 2009 Influenza A (H1N1) Virus Infection|journal=The New England Journal of Medicine|volume=362|location=[[New England Journal of Medicine]]|issue= 18|pages=1708–19|pmid=20445182|doi=10.1056/NEJMra1000449}}</ref> Even in the case of previously very healthy persons, a small percentage will develop [[pneumonia]] or [[acute respiratory distress syndrome]] (ARDS). This manifests itself as increased breathing difficulty and typically occurs 3–6 days after initial onset of flu symptoms.<ref name="WHObriefingnoteOct16">{{Cite news|url=http://www.who.int/csr/disease/swineflu/notes/h1n1_clinical_features_20091016/en/index.html|title=Clinical features of severe cases of pandemic influenza|date=16 October 2009|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO) |accessdate=25 October 2009|location=Geneva, Switzerland| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091025105555/http://www.who.int/csr/disease/swineflu/notes/h1n1_clinical_features_20091016/en/index.html| archivedate= 25 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref name=RongGongLinNov21>
{{Cite news
| url = http://www.latimes.com/features/health/la-me-flu-guidelines21-2009nov21,0,2717012.story?track=rss
| title = When to take a sick child to the ER
| newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]
| author=Rong-Gong Lin II
| date = 21 November 2009
| accessdate =4 January 2010
| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091125135818/http://www.latimes.com/features/health/la-me-flu-guidelines21-2009nov21,0,2717012.story?track=rss| archivedate= 25 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> The pneumonia caused by flu can be either direct viral pneumonia or a secondary bacterial pneumonia. In fact, a November 2009 ''[[New England Journal of Medicine]]'' article recommends that flu patients whose [[chest X-ray]] indicates pneumonia receive both antivirals and antibiotics.<ref>[http://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMoa0906695#t=articleTop Hospitalized Patients with 2009 H1N1 Influenza in the United States, April–June 2009], ''[[New England Journal of Medicine]]'', Jain, Kamimoto, ''et al.'', 12 November 2009. This study involved a total of 272 patients, which represents approximately 25% of U.S. hospitalized patients with lab-confirmed H1N1 whose cases were reported to the U.S. [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) from 1 May 2009, to 9 June 2009. The study found that "the only variable that was significantly associated with a positive outcome was the receipt of antiviral drugs within two days after the onset of illness" [Outcomes section, 2nd paragraph] and also that "only 73% of patients with radiographic evidence of pneumonia received antiviral drugs, whereas 97% received antibiotics." [Discussion section, 8th paragraph]. It is recommended that such patients receive both.</ref> In particular, it is a warning sign if a child (and presumably an adult) seems to be getting better and then relapses with high fever, as this relapse may be bacterial pneumonia.<ref name= DeniseGradySept3/>

Initially coined an "outbreak", the stint began in the state of [[Veracruz]], Mexico, with evidence that there had been an ongoing epidemic for months before it was officially recognized as such.<ref name=NYT6-23>{{Cite news| last = McNeil, Jr. | first = Donald G. | title = In New Theory, Swine Flu Started in Asia, Not Mexico |work=The New York Times | date = 23 June 2009 | url = http://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/24/health/24flu.html | accessdate =1 September 2009}}</ref> The Mexican government closed most of [[Mexico City]]'s public and private facilities in an attempt to contain the spread of the virus; however, it continued to spread globally, and clinics in some areas were overwhelmed by infected people. In June, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) and the U.S. CDC stopped counting cases and declared the outbreak a [[pandemic]].<ref name="MargaretChanJune11">{{Cite news|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2009/h1n1_pandemic_phase6_20090611/en/index.html|title=World now at the start of 2009 influenza pandemic|last=Chan|first=Dr. Margaret|date=11 June 2009|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO) |accessdate=25 October 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091022123810/http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2009/h1n1_pandemic_phase6_20090611/en/index.html| archivedate= 22 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

Despite being informally called "swine flu", the H1N1 flu virus cannot be spread by eating pork or pork products;<ref name="fluandyou"/><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/news/nation-and-world/la-na-pigs-flu5-2009dec05,0,6902061.story |title=Don't call it 'swine flu,' farmers implore |last=Huffstutter |first=P.J. |date=5 December 2009 |accessdate=5 December 2009 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> similar to other influenza viruses, it is typically contracted by person to person transmission through respiratory droplets.<ref name="cdc.gov">{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/recommendations.htm|title=Updated Interim Recommendations for the Use of Antiviral Medications in the Treatment and Prevention of Influenza for the 2009–2010 Season|date=7 December 2009|work=H1N1 Flu|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |accessdate=10 December 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091210205013/http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/recommendations.htm| archivedate= 10 December 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> Symptoms usually last 4–6 days.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/1673658-overview|title=H1N1 Influenza (Swine Flu)|last=Bronze|first=Michael Stuart|date=13 November 2009|work=eMedicine|publisher=Medscape|accessdate=10 December 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091227210136/http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/1673658-overview| archivedate= 27 December 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> [[Antivirals]] ([[oseltamivir]] or [[zanamivir]]) were recommended for those with more severe symptoms or those in an at-risk group.<ref name=CDCOct16AntiviralRecommendations/>

The pandemic began to taper off in November 2009,<ref name=WSJ-graph>{{cite news | url = http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748703429304575095743102260012.html |work=The Wall Street Journal | first=Betsy | last=Mckay | title=The Flu Season That Fizzled | date=2 March 2010| accessdate= 14 April 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> and by May 2010, the number of cases was in steep decline.<ref name="WHOMay14update">{{Cite news|url=http://www.who.int/csr/don/2010_05_14/en/index.html|title=Pandemic (H1N1) 2009 – update 100|date={{Nowrap|14 May}} 2010|work=Disease Outbreak News|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO) |accessdate=14 May 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100518163428/http://www.who.int/csr/don/2010_05_14/en/index.html| archivedate= 18 May 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref name="WHOIntensityMap">{{cite web|url=http://gamapserver.who.int/h1n1/qualitative_indicators/atlas.html?indicator=i2&date=Week%2017%20(26-Apr-2010%20:%2002-May-2010)|title=Global Intensity Map, Week 17 (April 26, 2010 – 2 May 2010)|work=Global Update on 2009 H1N1|publisher=World Health Organization (WHO) |accessdate=14 May 2010}}</ref><ref name="WHOSubtypeMap">{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/csr/disease/swineflu/FluTransmissionZones_2010_05_14.png |title=Percentage of respiratory specimens that tested positive for influenza: Status as of week 17 ({{Nowrap|25 April}} 25 – {{Nowrap|1 May}} 2010) |publisher=World Health Organization (WHO)  |accessdate=14 May 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100519020752/http://www.who.int/csr/disease/swineflu/FluTransmissionZones_2010_05_14.png| archivedate= 19 May 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref name="CDCInternational">{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/updates/international/|title=2009 H1N1 Flu: International Situation Update|date=7 May 2010|work=H1N1 Flu|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |accessdate=14 May 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100505140951/http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/updates/international/| archivedate= 5 May 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> On 10 August 2010, the Director-General of the WHO, [[Margaret Chan]], announced the end of the H1N1 pandemic,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euro.who.int/en/what-we-do/health-topics/communicable-diseases/influenza/news2/news/2010/08/who-director-general-declares-h1n1-pandemic-over |title=WHO/Europe &#124; WHO Director-General declares H1N1 pandemic over |publisher=World Health Organization (WHO) |date=10 August 2010 |accessdate=24 May 2011| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20110525050814/http://www.euro.who.int/en/what-we-do/health-topics/communicable-diseases/influenza/news2/news/2010/08/who-director-general-declares-h1n1-pandemic-over| archivedate= 25 May 2011 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> and announced that the H1N1 influenza event has moved into the post-pandemic period.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/csr/don/2010_09_10/en/index.html |title=WHO &#124; Influenza updates |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO) |date=10 September 2010 |accessdate=24 May 2011| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20110523201451/http://www.who.int/csr/don/2010_09_10/en/index.html| archivedate= 23 May 2011 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> According to the latest WHO statistics (July 2010), the virus has killed more than 18,000 people since it appeared in April 2009, however they state that the total mortality (including deaths unconfirmed or unreported) from the H1N1 strain is "unquestionably higher".<ref name="WHOMay14update"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.redorbit.com/news/health/1893907/h1n1_still_a_pandemic_says_who/|title=H1N1 Still A Pandemic, Says WHO|publisher=redOrbit|accessdate=10 August 2010}}</ref> Critics claimed the WHO had exaggerated the danger, spreading "fear and confusion" rather than "immediate information".<ref>{{Cite news|title=WHO admits errors in handling flu pandemic: Agency accused of overplaying danger of the virus as it swept the globe|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/36421914/|publisher=[[MSNBC]].com|date=12 April 2010| accessdate= 14 April 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> The WHO began an investigation to determine<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE5BL2ZT20100112 |title=WHO to review its handling of H1N1 flu pandemic |agency=Reuters |first=Johnathan |last=Lynn |date=12 January 2010| accessdate= 14 April 2011 <!--DASHBot-->| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20110326201246/http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE5BL2ZT20100112| archivedate= 26 March 2011| deadurl= no}}</ref> whether it had "frightened people unnecessarily".<ref name=UKTimes-waste>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/article7104253.ece|title=Swine flu pandemic declared by WHO was 'a waste of money'|publisher=The Times (UK)|date=22 April 2010 | location=London| accessdate= 14 April 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> A flu followup study done in September 2010, found that "the risk of most serious complications was not elevated in adults or children."<ref name="bloomberg.com">{{cite web|last=Randall |first=Tom |url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-07/swine-flu-in-children-is-no-more-severe-than-seasonal-virus-study-finds.html |title=Swine Flu In Children Found No More Severe Than Seasonal Virus |publisher=Bloomberg |date=7 September 2010 |accessdate=30 January 2011}}</ref> In an 5 August 2011 ''PLoS ONE'' article, researchers estimated that the 2009 H1N1 global infection rate was 11% to 21%, lower than what was previously expected.<ref>{{cite news|last=Roos|first=Robert|title=Study puts global 2009 H1N1 infection rate at 11% to 21%|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/cidrap/content/influenza/swineflu/news/aug0811serologic.html|newspaper=CIDRAP|date=8 August 2011| accessdate= 10 August 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> However, by 2012, a study showed that as many as 579,000 people could have been killed by the disease, as only those fatalities confirmed by laboratory testing were included in the original number, and meant that many of those without access to health facilities went uncounted. The majority of these deaths occurred in Africa and Southeast Asia. Experts agreed that an estimated 294,500 people were killed by the disease.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Dawood FS, Iuliano AD, Reed C, ''et al.'' |title=Estimated global mortality associated with the first 12 months of 2009 pandemic influenza A H1N1 virus circulation: a modelling study |journal=Lancet Infect Dis |volume=12 |issue=9 |pages=687–95 |year=2012 |month=September |pmid=22738893 |doi=10.1016/S1473-3099(12)70121-4 }}</ref><ref>First Global Estimates of 2009 H1N1 Pandemic Mortality Released by CDC-Led Collaboration CDC Spotlights http://www.cdc.gov/flu/spotlights/pandemic-global-estimates.htm</ref> The WHO also said that the initial death toll could be much higher.<ref>http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2164899/Swine-flu-killed-15-TIMES-number-people-reported-claims-international-study.html#ixzz1zXHh5Ky4</ref>

==Classification==
{{further2|[[Pandemic H1N1/09 virus#Nomenclature|Pandemic H1N1/09 virus: Nomenclature]]}}
The initial outbreak was called the "H1N1 influenza", or "Swine Flu" by American media. It is called [[pandemic H1N1/09 virus]] by the WHO,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/Pandemic_h1n1_presstranscript_2009_07_07.pdf|title=Transcript of virtual press conference with Dr Keiji Fukuda, Assistant Director-General ad Interim for Health Security and Environment, World Health Organization|date=7 July 2009|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO) |accessdate=26 October 2009}}</ref> while the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention refer to it as "novel influenza A (H1N1)" or "2009 H1N1 flu".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/guidance/cruiseships.htm|title=Interim Novel Influenza A (H1N1) Guidance for Cruise Ships |date=5 August 2009|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |accessdate=30 September 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091001112752/http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/guidance/cruiseships.htm| archivedate= 1 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> In the [[Netherlands]], it was originally called "Pig Flu", but is now called "New Influenza A (H1N1)" by the [[Netherlands National Institute for Public Health and the Environment|national health institute]], although the media and general population use the name "Mexican Flu". [[South Korea]] and [[Israel]] briefly considered calling it the "Mexican virus".<ref name="mexflu">{{Cite news|url=http://www.morungexpress.com/analysis/27870.html|title=SWINE FLU: A pandemic|last=Kikon|first=Chonbenthung S|work=The Morung Express|accessdate=28 September 2009}}{{dead link|date=September 2011}}</ref> Later, the South Korean press used "SI", short for "swine influenza". [[Taiwan]] suggested the names "H1N1 flu" or "new flu", which most local media adopted.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chinapost.com.tw/health/infectious-diseases/2009/04/29/206057/p2/Renamed-swine.htm |title=Renamed swine flu certain to hit Taiwan |date=28 April 2009 |work=The China Post |location=Taiwan (ROC)|accessdate=26 September 2009}}</ref> The [[World Organization for Animal Health]] proposed the name "North American influenza".<ref name="NYT 2009-04-28">{{Cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/29/world/asia/29swine.html |title=The naming of swine flu, a curious matter |last=Bradsher |first=Keith |date={{Nowrap|28 April}} 2009 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=29 April 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090502170810/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/29/world/asia/29swine.html?| archivedate= 2 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> The [[European Commission]] adopted the term "novel flu virus".<ref name="Guardian 28 April 2009">{{Cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2009/apr/28/mexican-swine-flu-pork-name |title=What's in a name? Governments debate 'swine flu' versus 'Mexican' flu |last=Pilkington |first=Ed |date={{Nowrap|28 April}} 2009 |work=The Guardian |location=UK |accessdate={{Nowrap|29 April}} 2009 | location=London}}</ref>

==Signs and symptoms==
The symptoms of H1N1 flu are similar to those of other [[influenza]]s, and may include  fever, cough (typically a "dry cough"), headache, [[Myalgia|muscle]] or [[Arthralgia|joint]] pain, [[Acute pharyngitis|sore throat]], [[Rigor (medicine)|chills]], [[fatigue (medical)|fatigue]], and [[Rhinorrhea|runny nose]]. [[Diarrhea]], vomiting, and [[neurology|neurological]] problems have also been reported in some cases.<ref name="CDC090724">{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/media/transcripts/2009/t090724.htm|title=CDC Briefing on Investigation of Human Cases of H1N1 Flu|date=24 July 2009|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |accessdate=28 July 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5jeG7e0IC|archivedate=8 September 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="CDCgeninfo">{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/guidance_homecare.htm|title=Interim Guidance for 2009 H1N1 Flu (Swine Flu): Taking Care of a Sick Person in Your Home|date=5 August 2009|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |accessdate=1 November 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091103194946/http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/guidance_homecare.htm| archivedate= 3 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> People at higher risk of serious complications include those aged over 65, children younger than 5, children with neurodevelopmental conditions, pregnant women (especially during the third trimester),<ref name="WHObriefingnoteOct16"/><ref name="AndrePicardNov1">{{Cite news|url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/life/health/h1n1-swine-flu/updated-reader-questions-on-h1n1-answered/article1329448/|title=Reader questions on H1N1 answered|last=Picard|first=Andre|date=1 November 2009| newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]]|accessdate=2 November 2009|location=Toronto, Canada| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091104040801/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/life/health/h1n1-swine-flu/updated-reader-questions-on-h1n1-answered/article1329448/| archivedate= 4 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref> and those of any age with underlying medical conditions, such as asthma, diabetes, obesity, heart disease, or a weakened immune system (e.g., taking [[immunosuppressive medications]] or infected with HIV).<ref name=NYT5-27>{{Cite news|last=Hartocollis |first=Anemona |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/28/health/policy/28flu.html |title='Underlying conditions' may add to flu worries | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=27 May 2009|accessdate=26 September 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090830210252/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/28/health/policy/28flu.html| archivedate= 30 August 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> More than 70% of hospitalizations in the U.S. have been people with such underlying conditions, according to the CDC.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB124502116646013713.html |title=Flu Pandemic Spurs Queries About Vaccine |last=Whalen |first=Jeanne|date=15 June 2009 | newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=31 August 2009 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5jeG3g2RN |archivedate=8 September 2009}}</ref>

In September 2009, the CDC reported that the H1N1 flu "seems to be taking a heavier toll among chronically ill children than the seasonal flu usually does."<ref name= DeniseGradySept3>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/04/health/research/04flu-001.html|title=Report Finds Swine Flu Has Killed 36 Children|last=Grady|first=Denise|date=3 September 2009| newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=17 September 2009}}</ref> Through 8 August 2009, the CDC had received 36 reports of paediatric deaths with associated influenza symptoms and laboratory-confirmed pandemic H1N1 from state and local health authorities within the United States, with 22 of these children having neurodevelopmental conditions such as [[cerebral palsy]], [[muscular dystrophy]], or [[developmental delay]]s.<ref name="CDCSept4">{{Cite news|url=http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5834a1.htm|title=Surveillance for Pediatric Deaths Associated with 2009 Pandemic Influenza A (H1N1) Virus Infection – United States, April–August 2009|date=4 September 2009|work=Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |accessdate=2 December 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091126022451/http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5834a1.htm| archivedate= 26 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> "Children with nerve and muscle problems may be at especially high risk for complications because they cannot cough hard enough to clear their airways".<ref name= DeniseGradySept3/> From 26 April 2009, to 13 February 2010, the CDC had received reports of the deaths of 277 children with laboratory-confirmed 2009 influenza A (H1N1) within the United States.<ref>[http://www.cdc.gov/flu/weekly/ 2009–2010 Influenza Season Week 6 ending 13 February 2010], CDC, Fluview: A Weekly Influenza Surveillance Report Prepared by the Influenza Division.</ref>

===Symptoms in severe cases===
The [[World Health Organization]] reports that the clinical picture in severe cases is strikingly different from the disease pattern seen during epidemics of seasonal influenza. While people with certain underlying medical conditions are known to be at increased risk, many severe cases occur in previously healthy people. In severe cases, patients generally begin to deteriorate around three to five days after symptom onset. Deterioration is rapid, with many patients progressing to respiratory failure within 24 hours, requiring immediate admission to an intensive care unit. Upon admission, most patients need immediate respiratory support with [[mechanical ventilation]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.who.int/csr/disease/swineflu/notes/h1n1_clinical_features_20091016/en/index.html|title=Clinical features of severe cases of pandemic influenza|date=16 October 2009|work=Pandemic (H1N1) 2009 briefing note 13|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO) |accessdate=17 January 2010|location=Geneva, Switzerland| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100119214956/http://www.who.int/csr/disease/swineflu/notes/h1n1_clinical_features_20091016/en/index.html| archivedate= 19 January 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

A November 2009 CDC recommendation stated that the following constitute "emergency warning signs" and advised seeking immediate care if a person experiences any one of these signs:<ref name="CDC_symptoms"/>
;In adults<nowiki>:</nowiki>
:* Difficulty breathing or shortness of breath
:* Pain or pressure in the chest or abdomen
:* Sudden dizziness
:* Confusion
:* Severe or persistent vomiting
:* Low temperature
;In children<nowiki>:</nowiki>
:* Fast breathing or working hard to breathe
:* Bluish skin color
:* Not drinking enough fluids
:* Not waking up or not interacting
:* Being so irritable that the child does not want to be held
:* Flu-like symptoms which improve but then return with fever and worse cough
:* Fever with a rash
:* Being unable to eat
:* Having no tears when crying

Research later indicated that the severe flu effects in healthy young and middle-aged adults are caused by an excessive immune response.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.physorg.com/news/2010-12-over-reactive-immune-young-adults-pandemic.html|title=Over-reactive immune system kills young adults during pandemic flu|date=5 December 2010|publisher=PhysOrg.com|accessdate=21 December 2010}}</ref>

==Complications==
Most complications have occurred among previously healthy individuals, with [[obesity]] and [[respiratory disease]] as the strongest risk factors. [[Pulmonary]] complications are common. Primary influenza [[pneumonia]] occurs most commonly in adults and may progress rapidly to acute lung injury requiring [[mechanical ventilation]]. Secondary [[bacterial infection]] is more common in children. ''[[Staphylococcus aureus]]'', including methicillin-resistant strains, is an important cause of secondary bacterial pneumonia with a high mortality rate. [[Neuromuscular]] and [[cardiac]] complications are unusual but may occur.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Rothberg |pmid=19935413 |first1=MB |last2=Haessler |first2=SD |title=Complications of seasonal and pandemic influenza |pages=e91–7 |issue=4 Suppl |volume=38 |journal=Critical Care Medicine |doi=10.1097/CCM.0b013e3181c92eeb|year=2010}}</ref>

A United Kingdom investigation of risk factors for hospitalisation and poor outcome with pandemic A/H1N1 influenza looked at 631 patients from 55 hospitals admitted with confirmed infection from May through September 2009. 13% were admitted to a high dependency or intensive care unit and 5% died; 36% were aged <16 years and 5% were aged ≥65 years. Non-white and pregnant patients were over-represented. 45% of patients had at least one underlying condition, mainly [[asthma]], and 13% received antiviral drugs before admission. Of 349 with documented chest x-rays on admission, 29% had evidence of [[pneumonia]], but bacterial co-infection was uncommon. Multivariate analyses showed that physician-recorded obesity on admission and pulmonary conditions other than asthma or [[chronic obstructive pulmonary disease]] (COPD) were associated with a severe outcome, as were radiologically confirmed pneumonia and a raised [[C-reactive protein]] (CRP) level (≥{{Nowrap|100 mg/l)}}. 59% of all in-hospital deaths occurred in previously healthy people.<ref>{{Cite journal|author=J.S. Nguyen-Van-Tam |title=Risk factors for hospitalisation and poor outcome with pandemic A/H1N1 influenza: United Kingdom first wave (May–September 2009) |journal=Thorax |volume=65 |pages=645–651 |year=2010 |url=http://thorax.bmj.com/content/65/7/645.full|accessdate=21 December 2010 |issue=7|author-separator=,|author2=P.J.M. Openshaw|author3=A. Hashim|display-authors=3|doi=10.1136/thx.2010.135210|pmid=20627925|last4=Gadd|first4=EM|last5=Lim|first5=WS|last6=Semple|first6=MG|last7=Read|first7=RC|last8=Taylor|first8=BL|last9=Brett|first9=SJ|pmc=2921287}}</ref>

[[Fulminant]] (sudden-onset) [[myocarditis]] has been linked to infection with H1N1, with at least four cases of myocarditis confirmed in patients also infected with A/H1N1. Three out of the four cases of H1N1-associated myocarditis were classified as fulminant, and one of the patients died.<ref>{{Cite journal|journal=[[Journal of the American College of Cardiology]]|volume=55 |last1=Bratincsák |issue=9 |pages=928–9 |first1=A |doi=10.1016/j.jacc.2010.01.004 |last2=El-Said |first2=HG |last3=Bradley |first3=JS |last4=Shayan |first4=K |last5=Grossfeld |first5=PD |last6=Cannavino |first6=CR |title=Fulminant Myocarditis Associated With Pandemic H1N1 Influenza A Virus in Children |pmid=20153131 |date=10 February 2010| laysummary=http://www.modernmedicine.com/modernmedicine/Modern+Medicine+Now/Myocarditis-Linked-to-Pandemic-H1N1-Flu-in-Childre/ArticleNewsFeed/Article/detail/656746?contextCategoryId=40137}} (primary source)</ref>
Also, there appears to be a link between severe A/H1N1 influenza infection and [[pulmonary embolism]]. In one report, five out of 14 patients admitted to the intensive care unit with severe A/H1N1 infection were found to have pulmonary emboli.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2009/10/091014111549.htm |title=Those With Severe H1N1 At Risk For Pulmonary Emboli, Researchers Find |publisher=ScienceDaily |date=18 October 2009 |accessdate=3 April 2010}}</ref>

An article published in ''[[JAMA (journal)|JAMA]]'' in September 2010<ref>{{cite doi|10.1001/jama.2010.1277}}</ref> challenged previous reports and stated that children infected in the 2009 flu pandemic were no more likely to be hospitalised with complications or get pneumonia than those who catch seasonal strains. Researchers found that about 1.5% of children with the H1N1 swine flu strain were hospitalised within 30 days, compared with 3.7% of those sick with a seasonal strain of H1N1 and 3.1% with an H3N2 virus.<ref name="bloomberg.com"/>

==Diagnosis==
Confirmed diagnosis of pandemic H1N1 flu requires testing of a [[nasopharyngeal]], nasal or [[oropharyngeal]] tissue swab from the patient.<ref name="specimen">{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/specimencollection.htm|title=Interim Guidance on Specimen Collection, Processing, and Testing for Patients with Suspected Novel Influenza A (H1N1) Virus Infection |date=13 May 2009|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |accessdate=23 November 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091126020551/http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/specimencollection.htm| archivedate= 26 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> [[Real-time polymerase chain reaction|Real-time]] [[RT-PCR]] is the recommended test as others are unable to differentiate between pandemic H1N1 and regular [[seasonal flu]].<ref name="specimen"/> However, most people with flu symptoms do not need a test for pandemic H1N1 flu specifically, because the test results usually do not affect the recommended course of treatment.<ref name="diagpub">{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/diagnostic_testing_public_qa.htm|title=Influenza Diagnostic Testing During the 2009–2010 Flu Season|date=29 September 2009|work=H1N1 Flu|publisher = [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |accessdate=23 November 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091126004503/http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/diagnostic_testing_public_qa.htm| archivedate= 26 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> The U.S. CDC recommend testing only for people who are hospitalised with suspected flu, pregnant women and people with weakened immune systems.<ref name="diagpub"/> For the mere diagnosis of influenza and not pandemic H1N1 flu specifically, more widely available tests include [[rapid influenza diagnostic test]]s (RIDT), which yield results in about 30 minutes, and [[direct fluorescent antibody|direct]] and indirect [[immunofluorescence]] assays ([[Direct fluorescent antibody|DFA]] and IFA), which take 2–4 hours.<ref name="diagnostic">{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/guidance/diagnostic_tests.htm|title=Interim Recommendations for Clinical Use of Influenza Diagnostic Tests During the 2009–10 Influenza Season|date=29 September 2009|work=H1N1 Flu|publisher = [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |accessdate=23 November 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091126022419/http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/guidance/diagnostic_tests.htm| archivedate= 26 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> Due to the high rate of RIDT [[false negative]]s, the CDC advises that patients with illnesses compatible with novel influenza A (H1N1) virus infection but with negative RIDT results should be treated empirically based on the level of clinical suspicion, underlying medical conditions, severity of illness and risk for complications, and if a more definitive determination of infection with influenza virus is required, testing with rRT-PCR or virus isolation should be performed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5830a2.htm|title=Evaluation of Rapid Influenza Diagnostic Tests for Detection of Novel Influenza A (H1N1) Virus --- United States, 2009|date=7 August 2009|work=Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report|publisher = [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |accessdate=5 December 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091217043745/http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5830a2.htm| archivedate= 17 December 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> Dr. Rhonda Medows of the [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] Department of Community Health states that the rapid tests are incorrect anywhere from 30% to 90% of the time and warns doctors in her state not to use them because they are wrong so often.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://abclocal.go.com/wjrt/story?section=news/health&id=7147447|title=Accuracy of rapid flu tests questioned|date=1 December 2009|work=HealthFirst|publisher=WJRT-TV/DT|accessdate=5 December 2009|location=Mid-Michigan, USA|agency=AP}}{{dead link|date=September 2011}}</ref> The use of RIDTs has also been questioned by researcher Paul Schreckenberger of the [[Loyola University Chicago|Loyola University]] Health System, who suggests that rapid tests may actually pose a dangerous [[public health]] risk.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.loyolamedicine.org/News/News_Releases/news_release_detail.cfm?var_news_release_id=973441074|title=Could Widely Used Rapid Influenza Tests Pose A Dangerous Public Health Risk? |date=17 November 2009|publisher=Loyola Medicine|accessdate=4 December 2009|location=Maywood, Illinois, U.S.}}</ref> Dr. Nikki Shindo of the WHO has expressed regret at reports of treatment being delayed by waiting for H1N1 test results and suggests, "[D]octors should not wait for the laboratory confirmation but make diagnosis based on clinical and epidemiological backgrounds and start treatment early".<ref name="NikkiShindoNov12"/>

On 22 June 2010, the CDC announced a new test called the "CDC Influenza 2009 A (H1N1)pdm Real-Time RT-PCR Panel (IVD)". It uses a molecular biology technique to detect influenza A viruses and specifically the 2009 H1N1 virus. The new test will replace the previous real-time RT-PCR diagnostic test used during the 2009 H1N1 pandemic, which received an emergency use authorisation from the U.S. [[Food and Drug Administration]] in April 2009. Tests results are available in four hours and are 96% accurate.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.cdc.gov/media/pressrel/2010/r100622.htm |title=New CDC Test to Detect Human Infections with the 2009 H1N1 Influenza Virus Authorized for Use by FDA |location=Atlanta |publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |date=22 June 2010 |accessdate=25 August 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100826205400/http://www.cdc.gov/media/pressrel/2010/r100622.htm| archivedate= 26 August 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

==Virus characteristics==
{{Main|Pandemic H1N1/09 virus}}
The virus was found to be a novel strain of influenza for which extant [[vaccination|vaccines]] against seasonal flu provided little protection. A study at the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention published in May 2009 found that children had no preexisting immunity to the new strain but that adults, particularly those older than 60, had some degree of [[immunity (medical)|immunity]]. Children showed no [[Cross-reactivity|cross-reactive]] [[antibody]] reaction to the new strain, adults aged 18 to 60 had 6–9%, and older adults 33%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/cidrap/content/influenza/swineflu/news/may2109serum-jw.html |title=Some immunity to novel H1N1 flu found in seniors |last=Schnirring |first=Lisa |date=21 May 2009 |publisher=Center for Infectious Disease Research & Policy |accessdate=26 September 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090923225423/http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/cidrap/content/influenza/swineflu/news/may2109serum-jw.html| archivedate= 23 September 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref name="CDC_MMWRDispatch_20090421">{{Cite news|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |url=http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm58d0421a1.htm |title=Swine Influenza A (H1N1) Infection in Two Children – Southern California, March–April 2009 |work=[[Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report]] |date={{Nowrap|21 April}} 2009 |accessdate=26 September 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090925183214/http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm58d0421a1.htm| archivedate= 25 September 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> While it has been thought that these findings suggest the partial immunity in older adults may be due to previous exposure to similar seasonal influenza viruses, a November 2009 study of a rural unvaccinated population in China found only a 0.3% cross-reactive antibody reaction to the H1N1 strain, suggesting that previous vaccinations for seasonal flu and not exposure may have resulted in the immunity found in the older U.S. population.<ref>{{Cite journal| last1 = Chen | first1 = H | last2 = Wang | first2 = Y | last3 = Liu | first3 = W | last4 = Zhang | first4 = J | last5 = Dong | first5 = B | last6 = Fan | first6 = X | last7 = De Jong | first7 = MD | last8 = Farrar | first8 = J | last9 = Riley | first9 = S | title = Serologic survey of pandemic (H1N1) 2009 virus, Guangxi Province, China | journal = Emerging Infectious Diseases | volume = 15 | issue = 11 | pages = 1849–50 | year = 2009 | pmid = 19891883 | pmc = 2857250 | doi=10.3201/eid1511.090868 }}</ref>

It has been determined that the strain contains genes from five different flu viruses: North American swine influenza, North American avian influenza, human influenza and two swine influenza viruses typically found in Asia and Europe. Further analysis has shown that several [[protein]]s of the virus are most similar to strains that cause mild symptoms in humans, leading [[virologist]] Wendy Barclay to suggest on 1 May 2009, that the initial indications are that the virus was unlikely to cause severe symptoms for most people.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/8028371.stm |title=What scientists know about swine flu |publisher=BBC News |author=Emma Wilkinson |date=1 May 2009|accessdate=26 September 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090929231136/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/8028371.stm| archivedate= 29 September 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

The virus is currently less lethal than previous pandemic strains and kills about 0.01–0.03% of those infected; the [[1918 flu pandemic|1918 influenza]] was about one hundred times more lethal and had a case fatality rate of 2–3%.<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Donaldson LJ |title=Mortality from pandemic A/H1N1 2009 influenza in England: public health surveillance study |journal=BMJ |volume=339 |pages=b5213 |year=2009 |pmid=20007665 |pmc=2791802 |doi=10.1136/bmj.b5213|author-separator=,|author2=Rutter PD|author3=Ellis BM|display-authors=3|last4=Greaves|first4=F. E C|last5=Mytton|first5=O. T|last6=Pebody|first6=R. G|last7=Yardley|first7=I. E}}</ref> By 14 November 2009, the virus had infected one in six Americans with 200,000 hospitalisations and 10,000 deaths – as many hospitalizations and fewer deaths than in an average flu season overall, but with much higher risk for those under 50. With deaths of 1,100 children and 7,500 adults 18 to 64, these figures "are much higher than in a usual flu season".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/nation-and-world/la-sci-swine-flu11-2009dec11,0,6351332.story|title=Swine flu has hit about one in six Americans, CDC says|first=Thomas H. II|last=Maugh|work=Los Angeles Times|date=11 December 2009|accessdate=13 December 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091213114305/http://www.latimes.com/news/nation-and-world/la-sci-swine-flu11-2009dec11,0,6351332.story| archivedate= 13 December 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

In June 2010, scientists from Hong Kong reported discovery of a new swine flu virus which is a hybrid of the pandemic H1N1 virus and viruses previously found in pigs. It is the first report of a reassortment of the pandemic virus, which in humans has been slow to evolve. Nancy Cox, head of the influenza division at the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, has said, "This particular paper is extremely interesting because it demonstrates for the first time what we had worried about at the very onset of the pandemic, and that is that this particular virus, when introduced into pigs, could reassort with the resident viruses in pigs and we would have new gene constellations. And bingo, here we are." Pigs have been termed the mixing vessel of flu because they can be infected both by avian flu viruses, which rarely directly infect people, and by human viruses. When pigs become simultaneously infected with more than one virus, the viruses can swap genes, producing new variants which can pass to humans and sometimes spread amongst them.<ref>{{Cite journal|journal=Science |date=18 June 2010 |volume=328 |issue=5985 |page=1529 |author=Vijaykrishna D, Poon LL, Zhu HC, Ma SK, Li OT, Cheung CL, Smith GJ, Peiris JS, Guan Y |title=Reassortment of pandemic H1N1/2009 influenza A virus in swine |pmid=20558710 |doi=10.1126/science.1189132 |bibcode=2010Sci...328.1529V}}</ref> "Unlike the situation with birds and humans, we have a situation with pigs and humans where there's a two-way street of exchange of viruses. With pigs it's very much a two-way street".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://edmonton.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20100618/swine-flu-virus-100618/20100618/?hub=EdmontonHome |title=H1N1 swaps genes with other pig viruses: scientists |date=18 June 2010 |publisher=CTV News |agency=[[The Canadian Press]]| accessdate= 14 April 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>

===Transmission===
Spread of the H1N1 virus is thought to occur in the same way that seasonal flu spreads. Flu viruses are spread mainly from person to person through coughing or sneezing by people with influenza. Sometimes people may become infected by touching something – such as a surface or object – with flu viruses on it and then touching their face. "Avoid touching your eyes, nose or mouth. Germs spread this way".<ref name="fluandyou">{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/H1N1flu/qa.htm|title=2009 H1N1 Flu ("Swine Flu") and You|date=10 February 2010|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |accessdate=26 February 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100304031110/http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/qa.htm| archivedate= 4 March 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

The [[basic reproduction number]] (the average number of other individuals whom each infected individual will infect, in a population which has no immunity to the disease) for the 2009 novel H1N1 is estimated to be 1.75.<ref>{{Cite journal|first1=Duygu |last1=Balcan |first2=Hao |last2=Hu |first3=Bruno |last3=Goncalves |first4=Paolo |last4=Bajardi |first5=Chiara |last5=Poletto |first6=Jose J.|last6=Ramasco|first7=Daniela|last7=Paolotti|first8=Nicola|last8=Perra |first9=Michele |last9=Tizzoni |date=14 September 2009|title=Seasonal transmission potential and activity peaks of the new influenza A(H1N1): a Monte Carlo likelihood analysis based on human mobility|journal=BMC Medicine |volume=7 |issue=45 |page=29 |doi=10.1186/1741-7015-7-45 |id= |pmid=19744314 |pmc=2755471 |arxiv=0909.2417v1}}</ref> A December 2009 study found that the transmissibility of the H1N1 influenza virus in households is lower than that seen in past pandemics. Most transmissions occur soon before or after the onset of symptoms.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=31 December 2009|title=Household Transmission of 2009 Pandemic Influenza A (H1N1) Virus in the United States|journal=[[New England Journal of Medicine]]|volume=361|issue=27|pages=2619–2627 |url=http://content.nejm.org/cgi/content/full/361/27/2619 |accessdate=21 December 2010|first1=Simon |last1=Cauchemez|first2=Christl A.|last2=Donnelly |first3=Carrie |last3=Reed| doi=10.1056/NEJMoa0905498|pmid=20042753|last4=Ghani|first4=Azra C.|last5=Fraser|first5=Christophe|last6=Kent|first6=Charlotte K.|last7=Finelli|first7=Lyn|last8=Ferguson|first8=Neil M.}}</ref>

The H1N1 virus has been transmitted to animals, including [[swine]], [[turkey (bird)|turkeys]], [[ferret]]s, household cats, at least one dog and a [[cheetah]].<ref>
