==Prevention==
{{See also|Influenza prevention|2009 flu pandemic vaccine|Influenza vaccine#2009-2010 Northern Hemisphere winter season}}
The H1N1 vaccine was initially in short supply and in the U.S., the CDC recommended that initial doses should go to priority groups such as pregnant women, people who live with or care for babies under six months old, children six months to four years old and health-care workers.<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://www.cdc.gov/mmWR/PDF/rr/rr5810.pdf
|title=Use of Influenza A (H1N1) 2009 Monovalent Vaccine: Recommendations of the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices (ACIP), 2009
|work=[[Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report]]
|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC)
|date=28 November 2009
|accessdate=2 November 2009
| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091103202202/http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/pdf/rr/rr5810.pdf| archivedate= 3 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> In the UK, the NHS recommended vaccine priority go to people over six months old who were clinically at risk for seasonal flu, pregnant women and households of people with compromised immunity.<ref name="nhs-april">{{Cite news
|url=http://www.nhs.uk/news/2009/04april/pages/swineflulatest.aspx
|title=Swine flu latest from the NHS
|date=25 September 2009
|work=NHS Choices
|publisher=[[National Health Services|NHS]]
|accessdate=28 September 2009
|agency=NHS Knowledge Service
| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091008013912/http://www.nhs.uk/News/2009/04April/Pages/swineflulatest.aspx| archivedate= 8 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

Although it was initially thought that two injections would be required, clinical trials showed that the new vaccine protected adults "with only one dose instead of two", and so the limited vaccine supplies would go twice as far as had been predicted.<ref name=NYT9-12-09>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/11/health/11vaccine.html |title=One Vaccine Shot Seen as Protective for Swine Flu|last=McNeil, Jr.|first=Donald G.|date=10 September 2009| newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | accessdate=17 September 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web
|url=http://www.who.int/csr/disease/swineflu/notes/briefing_20091030/en/index.html
|title=Experts advise WHO on pandemic vaccine policies and strategies
|date=30 October 2009
|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO)
|accessdate=2 November 2009
| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091102051824/http://www.who.int/csr/disease/swineflu/notes/briefing_20091030/en/index.html| archivedate= 2 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> Health officials worldwide were also concerned because the virus was new and could easily mutate and become more virulent, even though most flu symptoms were mild and lasted only a few days without treatment. Officials also urged communities, businesses and individuals to make contingency plans for possible school closures, multiple employee absences for illness, surges of patients in hospitals and other effects of potentially widespread outbreaks.<ref name="WSJ-7-18-09">{{Cite news
|url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB124787226825260533.html
|title=New Push in H1N1 Flu Fight Set for Start of School
|last=McKay
|first=Betsy
|date=18 July 2009
| newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]
|accessdate=31 August 2009
|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5jeG4aNty
|archivedate=8 September 2009
}}</ref>

In February 2010, the CDC's Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices voted for "universal" flu vaccination in the U.S. to include all people over six months of age. The 2010–2011 vaccine will protect against the 2009 H1N1 pandemic virus and two other flu viruses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/flu/about/qa/1011_vac_selection.htm |title=Vaccine Selection for the 2010–2011 Influenza Season |publisher=[[U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |accessdate=25 August 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20101006224851/http://www.cdc.gov/flu/about/qa/1011_vac_selection.htm| archivedate= 6 October 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

===Public health response===
{{See also|2009 flu pandemic by country}}
[[File:H1N1 map by confirmed cases.svg|thumb|{{legend|#550000|5,000+ confirmed cases}}{{legend|#8c0000|500+ confirmed cases}}{{legend|#d40000|50+ confirmed cases}}{{legend|#ff6666|5+ confirmed cases}}{{legend|#ff9999|1+ confirmed cases}}]]
On 27 April 2009, the [[European Union]] health commissioner advised Europeans to postpone nonessential travel to the United States or Mexico. This followed the discovery of the first confirmed case in Spain.<ref name="Guardian 27/4">{{Cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2009/apr/27/swine-flu-mexico|title=Europeans urged to avoid Mexico and US as swine flu death toll exceeds 100|date=27 April 2009|work=Guardian|accessdate=27 April 2009 | location=London | first=Daniel | last=Nasaw| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090430094402/http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2009/apr/27/swine-flu-mexico| archivedate= 30 April 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> On 6 May 2009, the [[Public Health Agency of Canada]] announced that their [[National Microbiology Laboratory]] (NML) had mapped the genetic code of the swine flu virus, the first time that had been done.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?art_id=nw20090506191835578C369647&click_id=31&set_id=1|title=H1N1 virus genome: 'This is a world first' |date=6 May 2009|work=Independent|accessdate=31 August 2009|author=AFP |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5jeF2dg9n |archivedate=8 September 2009}}</ref> In the U.K., the [[National Health Service]] launched a website, the National Pandemic Flu Service,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pandemicflu.direct.gov.uk/|title=National Pandemic Flu Service|publisher=NHS, NHS Scotland, NHS Wales, DHSSPS|accessdate=4 October 2009}}</ref> allowing patients to self-assess and get an authorisation number for antiviral medication. The system was expected to reduce the burden on [[general practitioner]]s.<ref name="nhs-april">{{cite web|url=http://www.nhs.uk/news/2009/04april/pages/swineflulatest.aspx |title=Swine flu latest |work=www.nhs.uk |accessdate=27 September 2009 | archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091008013912/http://www.nhs.uk/News/2009/04April/Pages/swineflulatest.aspx| archivedate= 8 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

U.S. officials observed that six years of concern about [[H5N1]] [[avian flu]] did much to prepare for the current H1N1 flu outbreak, noting that after H5N1 emerged in Asia, ultimately killing about 60% of the few hundred people infected by it over the years, many countries took steps to try to prevent any similar crisis from spreading further.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pe.com/localnews/rivcounty/stories/PE_News_Local_S_swineflu08.4301c9d.html|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5mqhyEUnt|archivedate=17 January 2010|title=Health officials evaluate response to swine flu|last=Hines|first=Lora|date=7 June 2009|work=Riverside Press-Enterprise|accessdate=17 September 2009}}</ref> The CDC and other U.S. governmental agencies<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/08/09/AR2009080902447.html|title=Preparing for Swine Flu's Return|last=Stein|first=Rob|date=10 August 2009|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=4 October 2009}}</ref> used the summer lull to take stock of the United States' response to H1N1 flu and attempt to patch any gaps in the [[public health]] safety net before flu season started in early autumn.<ref name="reuters20090604">{{Cite news|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idUSN0423008520090604?sp=true|title=As swine flu wanes, U.S. preparing for second wave|last=Steenhuysen|first=Julie|date=4 June 2009|agency=Reuters |accessdate=17 September 2009}}</ref> Preparations included planning a second influenza vaccination program in addition to that for seasonal influenza, and improving coordination between federal, state and local governments and private health providers.<ref name="reuters20090604"/> On 24 October 2009, U.S. President [[Barack Obama|Obama]] declared swine flu a national emergency, giving [[Secretary of Health and Human Services]] [[Kathleen Sebelius]] authority to grant waivers to requesting hospitals from usual federal requirements.<ref name="ObamaAuthorizesSebelius">{{Cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/10/24/AR2009102401061.html|title=President Obama declares H1N1 flu a national emergency|first1=Michael D.|last1=Shear|first2=Rob|last2=Stein|date=24 October 2009|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=25 October 2009}}</ref>

===Vaccines===
{{Main|2009 flu pandemic vaccine}}
[[File:A nurse vaccinates Barack Obama against H1N1.jpg|thumb|U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] being vaccinated against H1N1 flu on 20 December 2009.]]
{{As of|2009|11|19|df=UK}}, over {{Nowrap|65 million}} doses of vaccine had been administered in over 16 countries; the vaccine seems safe and effective, producing a strong immune response that should protect against infection.<ref name=Greenberg>{{Cite journal
| doi = 10.1056/NEJMoa0907413
| pages = 2405–13
| last = Greenberg
| first = Michael E.
| coauthors = Michael H. Lai, Gunter F. Hartel, Christine H. Wichems, Charmaine Gittleson, Jillian Bennet, Gail Dawson, Wilson Hu, Connie Leggio, Diane Washington, Russell L. Basser
| title = Response after One Dose of a Monovalent Influenza A (H1N1) 2009 Vaccine – Preliminary Report
| journal=N Engl J Med
| laysummary = http://www.time.com/time/health/article/0,8599,1921679,00.html
| year = 2009
| url = http://content.nejm.org/cgi/content/abstract/NEJMoa0907413v1
| volume = 361
| pmid=19745216
| issue=25
| accessdate= 14 April 2011 <!--DASHBot-->| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20110513103022/http://content.nejm.org/cgi/content/abstract/NEJMoa0907413v1| archivedate= 13 May 2011| deadurl= no}}</ref> Whereas the 2009 trivalent seasonal influenza vaccine neither increases nor decreases the risk of infection with H1N1, the vaccines rushed to combat the new strain are effective against H1N1,<ref>{{Cite journal|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |title=Effectiveness of 2008–09 trivalent influenza vaccine against 2009 pandemic influenza A (H1N1) – United States, May–June 2009 |journal=MMWR |volume=58 |issue=44 |pages=1241–5 |year=2009 |month=November |pmid=19910912 |url=http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5844a5.htm|author1=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC)| accessdate= 14 April 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|author=Hancock K |title=Cross-reactive antibody responses to the 2009 pandemic H1N1 influenza virus |journal=[[New England Journal of Medicine]] |volume=361 |issue=20 |pages=1945–52 |year=2009 |month=November |pmid=19745214 |doi=10.1056/NEJMoa0906453|author-separator=,|author2=Veguilla V|author3=Lu X|display-authors=3|last4=Zhong|first4=Weimin|last5=Butler|first5=Eboneé N.|last6=Sun|first6=Hong|last7=Liu|first7=Feng|last8=Dong|first8=Libo|last9=Devos|first9=Joshua R.}}</ref> although they are manufactured similarly. Overall the safety profile of the new H1N1 vaccine is similar to that of the seasonal flu vaccine, and as of November 2009 fewer than a dozen cases of [[Guillain-Barre syndrome]] had been reported post-vaccination.<ref name="MariePauleKienyNov19"/> Only a few of these were suspected to be actually related to the H1N1 vaccination, and only temporary illness had been observed.<ref name="MariePauleKienyNov19">{{Cite news|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/vpc_transcript_19_november_09_kieny.pdf|title=Transcript of virtual press conference with Dr Marie-Paule Kieny, Director, Initiative for Vaccine Research World Health Organization|date=19 November 2009|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO) |page=5|accessdate=22 November 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091129180427/http://www.who.int/mediacentre/vpc_transcript_19_november_09_kieny.pdf| archivedate= 29 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> This is in strong contrast to the [[1976 swine flu outbreak]], when mass vaccinations in the United States caused over 500 cases of Guillain-Barre syndrome and led to 25 deaths.<ref name="1976swine">{{Cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/apr/27/science/sci-swine-history27?pg=2|title=Swine flu 'debacle' of 1976 is recalled|last=Roan|first=Shari|date=27 April 2009|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=19 November 2009}}</ref> Although the vaccines were effective, many industrialised nations were giving away, selling, canceling orders for and destroying excess doses of the vaccine.<ref name=BusinessWeek-dump>[http://www.businessweek.com/globalbiz/content/apr2010/gb2010047_626290.htm Britain Slashed Swine Flu Vaccine Order], ''The Independent'', Alistair Dawber.</ref><ref>[http://topnews.us/content/215816-h1n1-vaccines-lie-unused-might-be-disposed H1N1 Vaccines Lie Unused, Might be Disposed], ''Top News'', Jason Ramsey, 04/08/2010.</ref>

There are safety concerns for people who are allergic to eggs because the viruses for the vaccine are grown in chicken-egg-based cultures. People with egg allergies may be able to receive the vaccine, after consultation with their physician, in graded doses in a careful and controlled environment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.infectioncontroltoday.com/hotnews/egg-allergy-and-flu-vaccines.html|title= Have Egg Allergy? You May Still Be Candidate for Flu Vaccines, Says Allergist|date=18 November 2009|work=Infection Control Today|publisher=Virgo Publishing|accessdate=22 November 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091121184521/http://www.infectioncontroltoday.com/hotnews/egg-allergy-and-flu-vaccines.html| archivedate= 21 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> A vaccine manufactured by Baxter is made without using eggs, but requires two doses three weeks apart to produce immunity.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/8325363.stm|title=GPs to receive swine flu vaccines|date=26 October 2009|work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |accessdate=22 November 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091029144308/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/8325363.stm| archivedate= 29 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

As of late November 2009, in Canada there had been 24 confirmed cases of [[anaphylactic shock]] following vaccination, including one death. The estimated rate is one anaphylactic reaction per 312,000 persons receiving the vaccine; however, six persons had suffered anaphylaxis out of 157,000 doses given from one batch of vaccine. Dr. David Butler-Jones, Canada's chief public health officer, stated that even though this was an [[adjuvant]]ed vaccine, that did not appear to be the cause of this severe allergic reaction in these six patients.<ref name=MichaelSmithNov30>[http://www.medpagetoday.com/PrimaryCare/Vaccines/17228 Canada Probes H1N1 Vaccine Anaphylaxis Spike], Michael Smith, North American Correspondent, MedPage Today, 30 November 2009.</ref><ref name="KeijiFukudaNov26">{{Cite news|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/vpc_transcript_26_november_09_fukuda.pdf|title=Transcript of virtual press conference with Kristen Kelleher, Communications Officer for pandemic (H1N1) 2009, and Dr Keiji Fukuda, Special Adviser to the Director-General on Pandemic Influenza|date=26 November 2009|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO) |accessdate=1 December 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091202231150/http://www.who.int/mediacentre/vpc_transcript_26_november_09_fukuda.pdf| archivedate= 2 December 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

A CDC study released Jan 28, 2013, estimated that the Pandemic H1N1 vaccine saved roughly 300 lives and prevented about 1 million illnesses. The study concluded that had the vaccination program started 2 weeks earlier, close to 60% more cases could have been prevented.<ref>{{cite news|last=Roos|first=Robert|title=CDC: Pandemic vaccine prevented 1 million cases, 300 deaths|url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/cidrap/content/influenza/swineflu/news/feb0113panvax.html|newspaper=CIDRAP|date=Feb 1, 2013}}</ref>

===Accusations of conflict of interest===
In January 2010, [[Wolfgang Wodarg]], a German deputy who trained as a physician and now chairs the health committee at the [[Council of Europe]], claimed major firms had organised a "campaign of panic" to put pressure on the [[World Health Organisation]] (WHO) to declare a "false pandemic" to sell vaccines. Wodarg said the WHO's "false pandemic" flu campaign is "one of the greatest medicine scandals of the century". He said that the "false pandemic" campaign began last May in [[Mexico City]], when a hundred or so "normal" reported influenza cases were declared to be the beginning of a threatening new pandemic, although he said there was little scientific evidence for this. Nevertheless he argued that the WHO, "in cooperation with some big pharmaceutical companies and their scientists, re-defined pandemics", removing the statement that "an enormous amount of people have contracted the illness or died" from its existing definition and replacing it by stating simply that there has to be a virus, spreading beyond borders and to which people have no immunity.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/world/swine-flu/story-e6frfkyi-1225818388508|title=Swine flu 'a false pandemic' to sell vaccines, expert says|date=13 January 2010|publisher=[[News.com]]|accessdate=13 January 2010 | first=Chris | last=Pollard| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100114013335/http://www.news.com.au/world/swine-flu/story-e6frfkyi-1225818388508| archivedate= 14 January 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref>

The WHO responded by stating that they take their duty to provide independent advice seriously and guarded against interference from outside interests. Announcing a review of the WHO's actions, spokeswoman Fadela Chaib stated: "Criticism is part of an outbreak cycle. We expect and indeed welcome criticism and the chance to discuss it".<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE5BL2ZT20100112 |agency=Reuters | title=WHO to review its handling of H1N1 flu pandemic | date=12 January 2010| accessdate= 14 April 2011 <!--DASHBot-->| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20110326201246/http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE5BL2ZT20100112| archivedate= 26 March 2011| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>Bloomberg http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601091&sid=ahj0H_RH8U68</ref> In March 2010, the [[Council of Europe]] launched an enquiry into "the influence of the pharmaceutical companies on the global swine flu campaign", and a preliminary report is in preparation.<ref>Paul Flynn, [http://assembly.coe.int/CommitteeDocs/2010/20100329_MemorandumPandemie_E.pdf The handling of the H1N1 pandemic: more transparency needed], memorandum, Social, Health and Family Affairs Committee, The [[Council of Europe]], 23 March 2010 (pdf)</ref>

On 12 April 2010, Keiji Fukuda, the WHO's top influenza expert, stated that the system leading to the declaration of a pandemic led to confusion about H1N1 circulating around the world, and he expressed concern that there was a failure to communicate in regard to uncertainties about the new virus, which turned out to be not as deadly as feared. WHO Director-General Margaret Chan has appointed 29 flu experts from outside the organization to conduct a review of WHO's handling of the H1N1 flu pandemic. She has told them, "We want a frank, critical, transparent, credible and independent review of our performance".<ref name=letter>{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2010/letter_bmj_20100608/en/index.html |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO) |author=Chan M |date=8 June 2010 |title=WHO Director-General's letter to BMJ editors|accessdate=30 January 2011| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20110130000141/http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2010/letter_bmj_20100608/en/index.html| archivedate= 30 January 2011 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

In June 2010, [[Fiona Godlee]], editor-in-chief of the ''[[BMJ]]'', published an editorial which criticised the WHO, saying that an investigation had disclosed that some of the experts advising WHO on the pandemic had financial ties with drug companies which were producing antivirals and vaccines.<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Fiona Godlee |title=Conflicts of interest and pandemic flu |journal=[[BMJ]] |volume=340 |pages=c2947 |year=2010 |url=http://www.bmj.com/content/340/bmj.c2947.full#ref-1|accessdate=21 December 2010|doi=10.1136/bmj.c2947 |pmid=20525680| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20101221213507/http://www.bmj.com/content/340/bmj.c2947.full| archivedate= 21 December 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> Margaret Chan, Director-General of the WHO, replied stating, "Without question, the ''BMJ'' feature and editorial will leave many readers with the impression that WHO's decision to declare a pandemic was at least partially influenced by a desire to boost the profits of the pharmaceutical industry. The bottom line, however, is that decisions to raise the level of pandemic alert were based on clearly defined virological and epidemiological criteria. It is hard to bend these criteria, no matter what the motive".<ref name=letter/> In August 2010, the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' printed an article stating that "a third of the experts advising the World Health Organisation about the swine flu pandemic had ties to drugs firms" and that of the 20 members of the Scientific Advisory Group for Emergencies, which advised the British Government on swine flu, 11 had done work for the pharmaceutical industry or were linked to it through their universities.<ref>{{cite news |title=Swine flu advisers' ties to drug firms: Five WHO experts linked with vaccine producers |author=Sophie Borland |newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] |date=13 August 2010 |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/health/article-1302505/WHO-swine-flu-advisers-ties-drug-firms-Experts-linked-vaccine-producers.html | accessdate= 10 September 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>

In June 2012, a study was published finding that the number of deaths related to the H1N1 influenza was fifteen times higher than the reported "laboratory confirmed" deaths.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.yahoo.com/h1n1-swine-flu-may-killed-15-times-more-202801465--abc-news-wellness.html |agency=ABC News Medical Unit | title=H1N1 Swine Flu May Have Killed 15 Times More Than First Said | date=26 June 2012}}, citing {{cite journal|journal=The Lancet Infectious Diseases |title=Estimated global mortality associated with the first 12 months of 2009 pandemic influenza A H1N1 virus circulation: a modelling study |author=Dawood FS, Iuliano AD, et al. |date=26 June 2012 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(08)61345-8 }}</ref>

===Infection control===

====Travel precautions====
[[Image:ChineseFluInspectors.JPG|thumb|Flu inspection on a flight arriving in China]]
[[Image:Airport Thermographic Camera.jpg|thumb|Thermal imaging camera and screen, photographed in an airport terminal in [[Greece]]. Thermal imaging can detect elevated body temperature, one of the signs of swine flu.]]
On 7 May 2009, the WHO stated that containment was not feasible and that countries should focus on mitigating the effect of the virus. They did not recommend closing borders or restricting travel.<ref name="WHO Travel">{{cite web
|url=http://www.who.int/csr/disease/swineflu/frequently_asked_questions/travel/en/index.html
|title=WHO – Influenza A(H1N1) – Travel
|date=7 May 2009
|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO)
|accessdate=17 June 2009
| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090618104753/http://www.who.int/csr/disease/swineflu/frequently_asked_questions/travel/en/index.html| archivedate= 18 June 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> On 26 April 2009, the [[Government of the People's Republic of China|Chinese government]] announced that visitors returning from flu-affected areas who experienced flu-like symptoms within two weeks would be quarantined.<ref name="reuters">{{Cite news
|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/europeCrisis/idUST344175
|title=FACTBOX-Asia moves to ward off new flu virus
|agency=Reuters
|date=9 February 2009
|accessdate=26 April 2009
| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090430041910/http://www.reuters.com/article/europeCrisis/idUST344175| archivedate= 30 April 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

U.S. airlines had made no major changes as of the beginning of June 2009, but continued standing practices which include looking for passengers with symptoms of flu, [[measles]] or other infections, and relying on in-flight [[air filter]]s to ensure that aircraft were sanitised.<ref name="airlines"/> Masks were not generally provided by airlines and the CDC did not recommend that airline crews wear them.<ref name="airlines"/> Some non-U.S. airlines, mostly Asian, including [[Singapore Airlines]], [[China Eastern Airlines]], [[China Southern Airlines]], [[Cathay Pacific]] and [[Mexicana Airlines]], took measures such as stepping up cabin cleaning, installing state-of-the-art air filters and allowing in-flight staff to wear face masks.<ref name="airlines">{{Cite news
|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/asiaCrisis/idUSN27536654
|title=Global airlines move to reduce infection risks
|last=Jacobs
|first=Karen
|date=3 June 2009
|agency=Reuters
|accessdate=17 September 2009
}}</ref>

====Schools====
U.S. government officials have been especially concerned about schools because the H1N1 flu virus appears to disproportionately affect young and school-age people, between six months and 24 years of age.<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://www.businesswire.com/portal/site/google/?ndmViewId=news_view&newsId=20090820006035&newsLang=en
|title=New CDC H1N1 Guidance for Colleges, Universities, and Institutions of Higher Education
|date=20 August 2009
|work=Business Wire
|accessdate=17 September 2009
}}</ref>
The H1N1 outbreak led to numerous precautionary school closures in some areas. Rather than closing schools, the CDC recommended that students and school workers with flu symptoms should stay home for either seven days total, or until 24 hours after symptoms subsided, whichever was longer.<ref name=24hours>{{Cite news
|url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/health/6557550.html
|title=Schools revamp swine flu plans for fall
|last=George
|first=Cindy
|date=1 August 2009
| newspaper=[[Houston Chronicle]]
|accessdate=31 August 2009
|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5jeG8PPyY
|archivedate=8 September 2009
}}</ref> The CDC also recommended that colleges should consider suspending fall 2009 classes if the virus began to cause severe illness in a significantly larger share of students than the previous spring. They also urged schools to suspend rules, such as penalties for late papers or missed classes or requirements for a doctor's note, to enforce "self-isolation" and prevent students from venturing out while ill;<ref>{{Cite news
|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/08/20/AR2009082003449.htm
|title=Colleges Warned About Fall Flu Outbreaks on Campus
|last=de Vise
|first=Daniel
|date=20 August 2009
| newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]
|accessdate=17 September 2009
}}</ref> schools were advised to set aside a room for people developing flu-like symptoms while they waited to go home and to have ill students or staff and those caring for them use face masks.<ref name="AJC8-14">{{Cite news|url=http://www.ajc.com/health/content/shared-auto/healthnews/flu-/630021.html|title=Get Smart About Swine Flu for Back-to-School|date=14 August 2009| newspaper=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|accessdate=31 August 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5jeG9XwyO|archivedate=8 September 2009}}</ref>

In California, school districts and universities were on alert and working with health officials to launch education campaigns. Many planned to stockpile medical supplies and discuss worst-case scenarios, including plans to provide lessons and meals for low-income children in case elementary and secondary schools closed.<ref name="swine-flu-goes-to-camp"/> [[University of California]] campuses stockpiled supplies, from paper masks and hand sanitizer to food and water.<ref name="swine-flu-goes-to-camp">
{{Cite news
| url=http://www.latimes.com/features/health/la-me-camp-flu27-2009jul27,0,5762666.story
| title=Swine flu goes to camp. Will it go to school next?
| last=Mehta
| first=Seema
| coauthors=Nicole Santa Cruz
| date=27 July 2009
| newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]
| accessdate=17 September 2009
}}</ref> To help prepare for contingencies, [[University of Maryland School of Medicine]] professor of [[pediatrics]] James C. King Jr. suggested that every county should create an "influenza action team" to be run by the local [[health department]], parents and school administrators.<ref>{{Cite news
|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/02/opinion/02king.html
|title=The ABC's of H1N1
|last=James C. Jr.
|first=King
|date=1 August 2009
| newspaper=[[The New York Times]]
|accessdate=17 September 2009
}}</ref> {{As of|2009|10|28}}, about 600 schools in the United States had been temporarily closed, affecting over 126,000 students in 19 states.<ref>{{Cite news
|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,570129,00.html
|title=H1N1 Closes Hundreds of Schools Across the U.S.
|date=28 October 2009
|publisher=Fox News
|accessdate=28 October 2009
| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091101132151/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,570129,00.html| archivedate= 1 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

====Workplace====
Fearing a worst-case scenario, the U.S. [[Department of Health and Human Services]] (HHS), the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention and the [[Department of Homeland Security]] (DHS) developed updated guidance<ref name="fluguidance"/> and a video for employers to use as they developed plans to respond to the H1N1 outbreak. The guidance suggested that employers consider and communicate their objectives, such as reducing transmission among staff, protecting people who are at increased risk of influenza-related complications from becoming infected, maintaining business operations, and minimising adverse effects on other entities in their [[supply chain]]s.<ref name="fluguidance">{{cite web
|url=http://www.flu.gov/plan/workplaceplanning/guidance.html
|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5jeGA4xE6
|archivedate=9 September 2009
|title=Business Planning
|work=Flu.gov
|publisher=U.S. Department of Health & Human Services
|accessdate=17 September 2009
}}</ref>

The CDC estimated that as much as 40% of the workforce might be unable to work at the peak of the pandemic due to the need for many healthy adults to stay home and care for an ill family member,<ref name="LATimes7-25">
{{Cite news
| url=http://www.latimes.com/features/health/la-sci-swine-flu25-2009jul25,0,3387335.story
| title=Swine flu could kill hundreds of thousands in U.S. if vaccine fails, CDC says
| first=Thomas H.
| last=Maugh II
| date=25 July 2009
| newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]
| accessdate=17 September 2009
}}</ref> and advised that individuals should have steps in place should a workplace close down or a situation arise that requires working from home.<ref name="Fox-7-17-09">{{Cite news
|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,533591,00.html
|title=Swine Flu: Why You Should Still Be Worried
|last=Fiore
|first=Marrecca
|date=17 July 2009
|publisher=Fox News
|accessdate=31 August 2009
|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5jeG55WpO
|archivedate=8 September 2009
}}</ref> The CDC further advised that persons in the workplace should stay home sick for seven days after getting the flu, or 24 hours after symptoms end, whichever is longer.<ref name=24hours/>

In the UK, the [[Health and Safety Executive]] (HSE) also issued general guidance for employers.<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://www.hse.gov.uk/news/2009/swineflu.htm
|title=Swine flu – HSE News Announcement
|publisher=Health and Safety Executive
|date=18 June 2009
|accessdate=31 August 2009
}}</ref>

====Facial masks====
[[Image:Swine Flu Masked Train Passengers in Mexico City.jpg|thumb|[[Mexico City Metro]]]]The U.S. CDC does not recommend use of face masks or [[respirator]]s in non-health care settings, such as schools, workplaces, or public places, with a few exceptions: people who are ill with the virus when around other people, and people who are at risk for severe illness while caring for someone with the flu.<ref name="cdcmasks">
{{Cite news
