====Pigs and food safety====
{{Main|2009 flu pandemic actions concerning pigs}}
The pandemic virus is a type of swine influenza, derived originally from a strain which lived in pigs, and this origin gave rise to the common name of "swine flu". This term is widely used by mass media. The virus has been found in American hogs,<ref>{{Cite news| last = Jordan | first = Dave | title = Minnesota Pig Tests Positive for H1N1 | url = http://www.newson6.com/Global/story.asp?S=11341148|publisher=KOTV|date=20 October 2009|accessdate=10 December 2009}}</ref> and Canadian<ref>{{Cite news| last = Evans | first = Brian | title = News Conference with Minister of Health and Chief Public Health Officer | url = http://www.phac-aspc.gc.ca/alert-alerte/h1n1/conferences/nc-2009-05-02-eng.php|date=5 May 2009|accessdate=10 December 2009|publisher=Public Health Agency of Canada| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091214162720/http://www.phac-aspc.gc.ca/alert-alerte/h1n1/conferences/nc-2009-05-02-eng.php| archivedate= 14 December 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> as well as in hogs in Northern Ireland, Argentina, and Norway.<ref>{{cite web| title = Human swine flu in pigs | url = http://scienceblogs.com/effectmeasure/2009/10/human_swine_flu_in_pigs.php|date=20 October 2009|accessdate=10 December 2009|work=Effect Measure| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091108035341/http://scienceblogs.com/effectmeasure/2009/10/human_swine_flu_in_pigs.php| archivedate= 8 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> Leading health agencies and the [[United States Secretary of Agriculture]] have stressed that eating properly cooked pork or other food products derived from pigs will not cause flu.<ref name=CDC_pork>{{cite press release|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2009/h1n1_20090430/en/index.html |title=Joint FAO/WHO/OIE Statement on influenza A(H1N1) and the safety of pork|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO) |date=7 May 2009|accessdate=26 September 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090923210159/http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/statements/2009/h1n1_20090430/en/index.html| archivedate= 23 September 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| last = Desmon | first = Stephanie | title = Pork industry rues swine flu | work=The Baltimore Sun | volume = 172 | issue = 233 | date = 21 August 2009 | pages = 1, 16 | url = http://www.baltimoresun.com/health/bal-md.hs.flu21aug21,0,5219798.story | accessdate =1 September 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5jeGAPswM|archivedate=8 September 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> Nevertheless, on 27 April, [[Azerbaijan]] imposed a ban on the importation of [[animal husbandry]] products from America.<ref name="trend">{{Cite news|url=http://news-en.trend.az/society/health/1462401.html|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5jfdFjpdm|archivedate=9 September 2009|publisher=[[Trend News Agency]]|title=Prevention against "swine flu" stabile in Azerbaijan: minister|date=28 April 2009|accessdate=28 April 2009}}</ref> The [[Indonesia]]n government also halted the importation of pigs and initiated the examination of {{Nowrap|9 million}} pigs in Indonesia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nasional.kompas.com/read/xml/2009/04/27/11120229/cegah.flu.babi.pemerintah.gelar.rapat.koordinasi|title=Cegah flu babi, pemerintah gelar rapat koordinasi|date=27 April 2009|work=Kompas newspaper| accessdate= 14 April 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> The Egyptian government ordered the slaughter of all pigs in Egypt on 29 April 2009.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2009/04/30/2556545.htm?section=justin%20Egypt%20orders%20pig%20cull|agency=AFP |title=Egypt orders pig cull|work=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=27 September 2009 |date=30 April 2009}}</ref>

==Treatment==
{{Further|Influenza treatment}}
A number of methods have been recommended to help ease symptoms, including adequate liquid intake and rest.<ref name=Mayo>{{cite web|url=http://www.mayoclinic.com/health/influenza/DS00081/DSECTION=treatments-and-drugs |author=Mayo Clinic Staff |publisher=[[Mayo Clinic]] |work=Diseases and Conditions |title=Influenza (flu) treatments and drugs |accessdate=20 May 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5jeG5VTNF|archivedate=8 September 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref> [[Over-the-counter drug|Over-the-counter]] pain medications such as [[acetaminophen]] and [[ibuprofen]] do not kill the virus; however, they may be useful to reduce symptoms.<ref name="Medline"/> [[Aspirin]] and other salicylate products should not be used by people under 19 with any flu-type symptoms because of the risk of developing [[Reye's Syndrome]].<ref name="National Reyes Syndrome Foundation">{{cite web|url=http://www.reyessyndrome.org/aspirin.html |publisher=[[National Reye's Syndrome Foundation]] |title=Aspirin / Salicylates and Reyes Syndrome| accessdate= 14 April 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>

If the fever is mild and there are no other complications, fever medication is not recommended.<ref name="Medline">{{cite web|url=http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/ency/article/003090.htm |publisher=[[U.S. National Library of Medicine]] |work=Medline Plus Medical Encyclopedia |title=Fever |accessdate=20 May 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090515173838/http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/ency/article/003090.htm| archivedate= 15 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> Most people recover without medical attention, although those with pre-existing or underlying medical conditions are more prone to complications and may benefit from further treatments.<ref name=CDC_symptoms>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/sick.htm |publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |title=What To Do If You Get Sick: 2009 H1N1 and Seasonal Flu |date=7 May 2009 |accessdate=1 November 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091103195142/http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/sick.htm| archivedate= 3 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

People in at-risk groups should be treated with [[antivirals]] (oseltamivir or zanamivir) as soon as possible when they first experience flu symptoms. The at-risk groups include pregnant and [[post partum]] women, children under two years old, and people with underlying conditions such as respiratory problems.<ref name=CDCOct16AntiviralRecommendations/> People who are not in an at-risk group who have persistent or rapidly worsening symptoms should also be treated with antivirals. People who have developed [[Pneumonia#Diagnosis|pneumonia]] should be given both antivirals and antibiotics, as in many severe cases of H1N1-caused illness, bacterial infection develops.<ref name="NikkiShindoNov12">{{Cite news|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/vpc_transcript_12_november_09_nikki_shindo.pdf|title=Transcript of virtual press conference with Gregory Hartl, Spokesperson for H1N1, and Dr Nikki Shindo, Medical Officer, Global Influenza Programme, World Health Organization|date=12 November 2009|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO) |accessdate=18 November 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091129180559/http://www.who.int/mediacentre/vpc_transcript_12_november_09_nikki_shindo.pdf| archivedate= 29 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> Antivirals are most useful if given within 48 hours of the start of symptoms and may improve outcomes in hospitalised patients.<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Jain S |title=Hospitalized patients with 2009 H1N1 influenza in the United States, April–June 2009 |journal=[[New England Journal of Medicine]] |volume=361 |issue=20 |pages=1935–44 |year=2009 |month=November |pmid=19815859 |doi=10.1056/NEJMoa0906695 |url=|author-separator=,|author2=Kamimoto L|author3=Bramley AM|display-authors=3|last4=Schmitz|first4=Ann M.|last5=Benoit|first5=Stephen R.|last6=Louie|first6=Janice|last7=Sugerman|first7=David E.|last8=Druckenmiller|first8=Jean K.|last9=Ritger|first9=Kathleen A.}}</ref> In those beyond 48 hours who are moderately or severely ill, antivirals may still be beneficial.<ref name="cdc.gov"/> If [[oseltamivir]] (Tamiflu) is unavailable or cannot be used, [[zanamivir]] (Relenza) is recommended as a substitute.<ref name=CDCOct16AntiviralRecommendations>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/recommendations.htm|title=Updated Interim Recommendations for the Use of Antiviral Medications in the Treatment and Prevention of Influenza for the 2009–2010 Season|date=8 September 2009|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |accessdate=17 September 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090917030300/http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/recommendations.htm| archivedate= 17 September 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref name="WHOAug21antiviralrecommendations">{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/csr/disease/swineflu/notes/h1n1_use_antivirals_20090820/en/index.html|title=Recommended use of antivirals|date=21 August 2009|work=Global Alert and Response (GAR)|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO) |accessdate=6 November 2009|location=Geneva| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091104171524/http://www.who.int/csr/disease/swineflu/notes/h1n1_use_antivirals_20090820/en/index.html| archivedate= 4 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> [[Peramivir]] is an experimental [[antiviral drug]] approved for hospitalised patients in cases where the other available methods of treatment are ineffective or unavailable.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/emergency-use-authorization-granted-for-biocrysts-peramivir-65876107.html|title=Emergency Use Authorization Granted For BioCryst's Peramivir |date=23 October 2009 |publisher=PRNewswire|accessdate=30 January 2011 |agency=PRNewswire-FirstCall}}</ref>

To help avoid shortages of these drugs, the U.S. CDC recommended oseltamivir treatment primarily for people hospitalised with pandemic flu; people at risk of serious flu complications due to underlying medical conditions; and patients at risk of serious flu complications. The CDC warned that the indiscriminate use of antiviral medications to prevent and treat influenza could ease the way for [[drug-resistant]] strains to emerge, which would make the fight against the pandemic that much harder. In addition, a British report found that people often failed to complete a full course of the drug or took the medication when not needed.<ref name=Tami1>{{Cite news|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/economy/ap/53932902.html|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5jCd175C5|archivedate=21 August 2009|title=WHO: Healthy people who get swine flu don't need Tamiflu; drug for young, old, pregnant|last=Cheng|first=Maria|date=21 August 2009|work=[[Washington Examiner]]|accessdate=17 September 2009}}</ref>

===Side effects===
Both medications have known side effects, including lightheadedness, chills, nausea, vomiting, loss of appetite and trouble breathing. Children were reported to be at increased risk of self-injury and confusion after taking oseltamivir.<ref name=Mayo/> The WHO warn against buying antiviral medications from online sources, and estimate that half the drugs sold by online pharmacies without a physical address are counterfeit.<ref name=onlinedrugs>{{Cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/besttreatments/2009/may/08/warning-against-buying-flu-drugs-online |title=Warning against buying flu drugs online |work=The Guardian |location=UK |author=BMJ Group |date=8 May 2009|accessdate=26 September 2009 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>

===Resistance===
{{As of|2010|12|df=US}}, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) reported 314 samples of the 2009 pandemic H1N1 flu tested worldwide have shown resistance to [[oseltamivir]] ([[Tamiflu]]).<ref name="Update on oseltamivir resistance to influenza H1N1 (2009) viruses">
{{cite web
|url=http://www.who.int/csr/disease/influenza/2010_12_15_weekly_web_update_oseltamivir_resistance.pdf
|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5w6to3rzf
|archivedate=30 January 2011
| title=Update on oseltamivir resistance to influenza H1N1 (2009) viruses
| publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO)
| date= 15 December 2010
| accessdate=30 December 2010
}}</ref> This is not totally unexpected as 99.6% of the seasonal H1N1 flu strains tested have developed resistance to oseltamivir.<ref>
{{cite web
| url=http://www.cdc.gov/flu/weekly/weeklyarchives2008-2009/weekly39.htm
| title=2008–2009 Influenza Season Week 39 ending October 3, 2009
| publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC)
| date=9 October 2009
| accessdate=20 November 2009
| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091103234144/http://www.cdc.gov/flu/weekly/weeklyarchives2008-2009/weekly39.htm| archivedate= 3 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> No circulating flu has yet shown any resistance to [[zanamivir]] ([[Relenza]]), the other available anti-viral.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web| url=http://www.cdc.gov/flu/weekly/weeklyarchives2008-2009/weekly32.htm| title=2008–2009 Influenza Season Week 32 ending August 15, 2009| work=Flu Activity & Surveillance| publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) | date=21 August 2009 |accessdate=4 December 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091103235431/http://www.cdc.gov/flu/weekly/weeklyarchives2008-2009/weekly32.htm| archivedate= 3 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

===Effectiveness of antivirals questioned===
On 8 December 2009, the [[Cochrane Collaboration]], which reviews medical evidence, announced in a review published in ''[[BMJ]]'' that it had reversed its previous findings that the antiviral drugs [[oseltamivir]] (Tamiflu) and [[zanamivir]] (Relenza) can ward off [[pneumonia]] and other serious conditions linked to influenza. They reported that an analysis of 20 studies showed oseltamivir offered mild benefits for healthy adults if taken within 24 hours of onset of symptoms, but found no clear evidence it prevented lower respiratory tract infections or other [[complication (medicine)|complications]] of influenza.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601100&sid=a9acc7qIJFdU|title=Roche's Tamiflu Not Proven to Cut Flu Complications, Study Says|last=Cortez|first=Michelle Fay|date=9 December 2009|publisher=Bloomberg L.P|accessdate=11 December 2009}}</ref><ref name=BMJDec8>{{Cite journal|date=8 December 2009|title=Neuraminidase inhibitors for preventing and treating influenza in healthy adults: systematic review and meta-analysis|journal=BMJ|publisher=BMJ Publishing Group Ltd.|url=http://www.bmj.com/cgi/content/abstract/339/dec07_2/b5106?ijKey=b9e57312b08cf03c1923f6a254048e5d5a08e60d&keytype2=tf_ipsecsha|accessdate=11 December 2009|doi=10.1136/bmj.b5106|first1=Tom |last1=Jefferson |first2=Mark |last2=Jones |first3=Peter |last3=Doshi |first4=Chris |last4=Del Mar|volume=339|pages=b5106|pmid=19995812|pmc=2790574}}</ref> Their published finding relates only to its use in healthy adults with influenza; they say nothing about its use in patients judged to be at high risk of complications (pregnant women, children under five and those with underlying medical conditions), and uncertainty over its role in reducing complications in healthy adults may still leave it as a useful drug for reducing the duration of symptoms. The drugs might eventually be demonstrated to be effective against flu-related complications; in general, the Cochrane Collaboration concluded "Paucity of good data".<ref name=BMJDec8/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Godlee|first=Fiona|date=10 December 2009|title=We want raw data, now|journal=BMJ|publisher=BMJ Publishing Group Ltd.|url=http://www.bmj.com/cgi/content/full/339/dec10_2/b5405|doi=10.1136/bmj.b5405|volume=339|pages=b5405| accessdate= 14 April 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>

Some specific results from the ''BMJ'' article include: "The efficacy of oral oseltamivir against symptomatic laboratory confirmed influenza was 61% (risk ratio 0.39, 95% confidence interval 0.18 to 0.85) at {{Nowrap|75 mg}} daily&nbsp;... The remaining evidence suggests oseltamivir did not reduce influenza related lower respiratory tract complications (risk ratio 0.55, 95% confidence interval 0.22 to 1.35)".<ref name=BMJDec8/> Notice especially the wide range for this second result.

==Epidemiology==
{{Further|2009 flu pandemic timeline|2009 flu pandemic tables|2009 flu pandemic by country}}
{{2009 flu pandemic data}}
While it is not known precisely where or when the virus originated,<ref name=Nature>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.nature.com/news/2009/090505/full/459014a/box/1.html|title=The turbulent history of the A(H1N1) virus |first=Hayden Erica |last=Check |date=5 May 2009 |journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]] |accessdate=7 May 2009 |doi=10.1038/459014a |issn=1744-7933|format=fee required |volume=459 |pmid=19424121 |issue=7243|pages=14–5| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090510124851/http://www.nature.com/news/2009/090505/full/459014a/box/1.html| archivedate= 10 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite video |people= Larry Pope |title= Smithfield Foods CEO on flu virus |url= http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/21134540/vp/30523283#30523283 |format= flv |medium= Television production |publisher=[[MSNBC]] |accessdate =16 September 2009}}</ref> analyses in scientific journals have suggested that the H1N1 strain responsible for the 2009 outbreak first evolved in September 2008 and circulated amongst humans for several months before being formally recognised and identified as a novel strain of influenza.<ref name=Nature/><ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/full/324/5927/572 |title=As Swine Flu Circles Globe, Scientists Grapple With Basic Questions |journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |author=Cohen Jon, Enserink Martin |date=1 May 2009|accessdate=26 September 2009|volume=324|issue=5927|pages=572–3|format=fee required|doi=10.1126/science.324_572 |pmid=19407164| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090925121651/http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/full/324/5927/572| archivedate= 25 September 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

===Mexico===
{{Further|2009 flu pandemic in Mexico}}

The virus was first reported in two U.S. children in March 2009, but health officials have reported that it apparently infected people as early as January 2009 in Mexico.<ref name="Reuters6-11">{{Cite news |url=http://www.reuters.com/article/middleeastCrisis/idUSN11399103 |title=New flu has been around for years in pigs – study |last=Fox |first=Maggie |date=11 June 2009 |agency=Reuters |accessdate=17 September 2009}}</ref> The outbreak was first detected in [[Mexico City]] on 18 March 2009;<ref name="NYT4-26">{{Cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/27/health/27questions.html|title=Flu Outbreak Raises a Set of Questions |first=Donald G. |last=McNeil Jr.|date=26 April 2009|work=The New York Times|accessdate=17 September 2009}}</ref> immediately after the outbreak was officially announced, Mexico notified the U.S. and World Health Organization, and within days of the outbreak Mexico City was "effectively shut down".<ref name=Fox5-12>{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,519902,00.html|title=Study: Mexico Has Thousands More Swine Flu Cases|date=12 May 2009|publisher=[[Fox News]] Network|accessdate=17 September 2009|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Some countries cancelled flights to Mexico while others halted trade. Calls to close the border to contain the spread were rejected.<ref name=Fox5-12/> Mexico already had hundreds of non-lethal cases before the outbreak was officially discovered, and was therefore in the midst of a "silent epidemic". As a result, Mexico was reporting only the most serious cases which showed more severe signs different from those of normal flu, possibly leading to a skewed initial estimate of the case fatality rate.<ref name=NYT4-26/>

===United States===
{{Further|2009 flu pandemic in the United States}}
The new strain was first identified by the CDC in two children, neither of whom had been in contact with pigs. The first case, from [[San Diego County, California]], was confirmed from clinical specimens ([[nasopharynx|nasopharyngeal]] [[Cotton swab|swab]]) examined by the CDC on 14 April 2009. A second case, from nearby [[Imperial County, California]], was confirmed on 17 April. The patient in the first confirmed case had flu symptoms including fever and cough on clinical examination on 30 March, and the second on 28 March.<ref name="mmwr5815a5">{{cite journal|url=http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5815a5.htm|title=Swine Influenza A (H1N1) Infection in Two Children --- Southern California, March–April 2009|date=24 April 2009|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |work=[[Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report]]|volume=58 (Dispatch)|issue=15|pages=400–402|accessdate=4 October 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091001131355/http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5815a5.htm| archivedate= 1 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

The first confirmed H1N1/09 pandemic flu death, which occurred at [[Texas Children's Hospital]] in Houston, Texas, was of a toddler from Mexico City who was visiting family in [[Brownsville, Texas]], before being air-lifted to Houston for treatment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://abclocal.go.com/ktrk/story?section=news/health&id=6786416&rss=rss-ktrk-article-6786416|title=Swine flu victim dies in Houston|date=29 April 2009|publisher=KTRK-TV/DT|accessdate=18 November 2009|location=Houston, Texas|agency=AP}}</ref>

===Data reporting and accuracy<!-- This section is linked to by Template:2009 flu pandemic menu -->===
{{See also|GISAID|National Influenza Centers|Disease surveillance|Clinical surveillance}}
Influenza surveillance information "answers the questions of where, when, and what influenza viruses are circulating. It can be used to determine if influenza activity is increasing or decreasing, but cannot be used to ascertain how many people have become ill with influenza".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/flu/weekly/fluactivity.htm|title=Flu Activity & Surveillance|date=30 November 2009|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |accessdate=2 December 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091126143103/http://www.cdc.gov/flu/weekly/fluactivity.htm| archivedate= 26 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> For example, as of late June 2009, influenza surveillance information showed the U.S. had nearly 28,000 laboratory-confirmed cases including 3,065 hospitalisations and 127 deaths; but mathematical modelling showed an estimated {{Nowrap|1 million}} Americans currently had the 2009 pandemic flu, according to Lyn Finelli, a flu surveillance official with the CDC.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/06/25/us-swine-flu-cases-may-ha_n_221240.html|title=US Swine Flu Cases May Have Hit {{Nowrap|1 Million}}|last=Stobbe|first=Mike|date=25 June 2009|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=2 December 2009|agency=AP}}</ref> Estimating deaths from influenza is also a complicated process. In 2005, influenza only appeared on the death certificates of 1,812 people in the US. The average annual US death toll from flu is, however, estimated to be 36,000.<ref name="Ellenberg">{{Cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/id/2218367/|title=Influenza Body Count|last=Ellenberg|first=Jordan|date=4 July 2009|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|accessdate=2 December 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100115031919/http://www.slate.com/id/2218367/?| archivedate= 15 January 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> The CDC explains:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/flu/about/disease/us_flu-related_deaths.htm|title=Questions and Answers Regarding Estimating Deaths from Influenza in the United States|date=4 September 2009|work=Seasonal Influenza (Flu)|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |accessdate={{Nowrap|2 December}} 2009}}</ref> "[I]nfluenza is infrequently listed on death certificates of people who die from flu-related complications" and hence, "Only counting deaths where influenza was included on a death certificate would be a gross underestimation of influenza's true impact".

Influenza surveillance information on the 2009 H1N1 flu pandemic is available, but almost no studies attempted to estimate the total number of deaths attributable to H1N1 flu. Two studies were carried out by the CDC; the later of them estimated that between 7,070 and 13,930 deaths were attributable to H1N1 flu from April to 14 November 2009.<ref name="WHOestimateNov">{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/estimates_2009_h1n1.htm|title=CDC Estimates of 2009 H1N1 Influenza Cases, Hospitalizations and Deaths in the United States, April – December 12, 2009|date=15 January 2010|work=H1N1 Flu|publisher=CDC|accessdate=17 January 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100119201425/http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/estimates_2009_h1n1.htm| archivedate= 19 January 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> During the same period, 1642 deaths were officially confirmed as caused by H1N1 flu.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/flu/weekly/weeklyarchives2009-2010/weekly45.htm|title=CDC week 45|date=14 November 2009|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |accessdate={{Nowrap|14 December}} 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/flu/weekly/weeklyarchives2008-2009/weekly34.htm|title=CDC week 34|date=30 August 2009|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |accessdate={{Nowrap|14 December}} 2009}}</ref> The WHO state that total mortality (including deaths unconfirmed or unreported) from H1N1 flu is "unquestionably higher" than their own confirmed death statistics.<ref name="WHOstatement">{{Cite news|url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601124&sid=akODnI6cicxw|first=Jason|last=Gale|title=Clinical features of severe cases of pandemic influenza|date=4 December 2009|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]|accessdate=4 December 2009}}</ref>

The initial outbreak received a week of near-constant media attention. [[Epidemiologist]]s cautioned that the number of cases reported in the early days of an outbreak can be very inaccurate and deceptive due to several causes, among them [[selection bias]], [[media bias]] and incorrect reporting by governments. Inaccuracies could also be caused by authorities in different countries looking at differing population groups. Furthermore, countries with poor health care systems and older laboratory facilities may take longer to identify or report cases.<ref>{{Cite news |agency=[[Reuters]] |url=http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/IRIN/2687d9562c28b487c30aca4e889c5e93.htm |title=GLOBAL: No A (H1N1) cases – reality or poor lab facilities? |date=8 May 2009 |accessdate=9 May 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090511130411/http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/IRIN/2687d9562c28b487c30aca4e889c5e93.htm| archivedate= 11 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> "[E]ven in developed countries the [numbers of flu deaths] are uncertain, because medical authorities don't usually verify who actually died of influenza and who died of a flu-like illness".<ref>{{Cite journal|first1=Peter M. |last1=Sandman |first2=Jody |last2=Lanard|year=2005|title=Bird Flu: Communicating the Risk|journal=Perspectives in Health Magazine|volume=10|issue=2|url=http://www.paho.org/English/DD/PIN/Number22_article1a.htm| accessdate= 14 April 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> Dr. Joseph S. Bresee (the CDC flu division's epidemiology chief) and Dr. [[Michael Osterholm]] (director of the [[Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy]]) have pointed out that millions of people have had H1N1 flu, usually in a mild form, so the numbers of laboratory-confirmed cases were actually meaningless, and in July 2009 the WHO stopped keeping count of individual cases and focused more on major outbreaks.<ref name=WHO-Briefing-Note-3>{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/csr/disease/swineflu/notes/h1n1_surveillance_20090710/en/index.html|title=Pandemic (H1N1) 2009 briefing note 3|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO) |language=2009-07-16 |accessdate=17 July 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090722084146/http://www.who.int/csr/disease/swineflu/notes/h1n1_surveillance_20090710/en/index.html| archivedate= 22 July 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

===Followup===
A Wisconsin study published in the ''[[Journal of the American Medical Association]]'' in September 2010, reported that findings showed that the 2009 H1N1 flu was no more severe than the seasonal flu. "The risk of most serious complications was not elevated in adults or children", the study's authors wrote. "Children were disproportionately affected by 2009 H1N1 infection, but the perceived severity of symptoms and risk of serious outcomes were not increased." Children infected in the 2009 H1N1 flu pandemic were no more likely to be hospitalized with complications or get pneumonia than those who catch seasonal strains. About 1.5% of children with the H1N1 swine flu strain were hospitalized within 30 days, compared with 3.7% of those sick with a seasonal strain of H1N1 and 3.1% with an H3N2 virus.<ref>{{cite web|last=Randall |first=Tom |url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-07/swine-flu-in-children-is-no-more-severe-than-seasonal-virus-study-finds.html |title=Swine Flu Found No More Severe Than Seasonal Virus |publisher=Bloomberg |date=7 September 2010 |accessdate=24 May 2011}}</ref>

CDC illness and death estimates from April 2009 to April 2010, are as follows:
* CDC estimates that between 43&nbsp;million and 89&nbsp;million cases of 2009 H1N1 occurred between April 2009 and 10 April 2010. The mid-level in this range is about 61&nbsp;million people infected with 2009 H1N1.
* CDC estimates that between about 195,000 and 403,000 H1N1-related hospitalizations occurred between April 2009 and 10 April 2010. The mid-level in this range is about 274,000 2009 H1N1-related hospitalizations.
* CDC estimates that between about 8,870 and 18,300 2009 H1N1-related deaths occurred between April 2009 and 10 April 2010. The mid-level in this range is about 12,470 2009 H1N1-related deaths.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/h1n1flu/estimates_2009_h1n1.htm |title=Updated CDC Estimates of 2009 H1N1 Influenza Cases, Hospitalizations and Deaths in the United States, April 2009 – April 10, 2010 |publisher=Cdc.gov |accessdate=24 May 2011}}</ref>

It is often stated that about 36,000 die from the seasonal flu in the U.S. each year,<ref>{{cite web|last=Mason |first=Michael |url=http://health.nytimes.com/health/guides/disease/the-flu/overview.html |title=Flu – Symptoms, Diagnosis, Treatment of Flu – NY Times Health Information |publisher=Health.nytimes.com |accessdate=24 May 2011}}</ref> and this is frequently understood as an indication that the H1N1 strain was not as severe as seasonal influenza. The 36,000 estimate was presented in a 2003 study by CDC scientists published in the ''Journal of the American Medical Association'' but only refers to a period from 1990-91 through 1998-99. During those years, the number of estimated deaths ranged from 17,000 to 52,000, with an average of about 36,000. The ''JAMA'' study also looked at seasonal influenza-associated deaths over a 23 year period, from 1976-1977 and 1998-1999. During that period, estimates of respiratory and circulatory influenza-associated deaths ranged from about 5,000 to about 52,000, with an average of about 25,000. While the 36,000 number is often cited, it's important to note that during that decade, influenza A (H3N2) was the predominant virus during most of the seasons, and H3N2 influenza viruses are typically associated with higher death rates. CDC believes that the range of deaths over the past 31 years (~3,000 to ~49,000) is a more accurate representation of the unpredictability and variability of flu-associated deaths.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.gov/flu/about/disease/us_flu-related_deaths.htm#how-many-die |title=CDC - Seasonal Influenza (Flu) - Questions and Answers Regarding Estimating Deaths from Influenza in the United States |publisher=Cdc.gov |date= |accessdate=23 October 2011}}</ref> The annual toll from seasonal influenza in the US is more accurately estimated at 3000-49,000 deaths per year. So the H1N1 pandemic estimated mortality of 8,870 to 18,300, places it in the mid-range of estimates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://flu.gov/individualfamily/about/h1n1/estimates_2009_h1n1.html#The%20Numbers |title=CDC Estimates of 2009 H1N1 Influenza Cases, Hospitalizations and Deaths in the United States, April – November 14, 2009 |publisher=Flu.gov |date= |accessdate=23 October 2011}}</ref>

The 2009 pandemic caused hospitals around the country to make significant preparations in terms of hospital surge capacities, especially within the emergency department and among vulnerable populations.  In many cases, hospitals were relatively successful in making sure that those patients most severely affected by the influenza strain were able to be seen, treated, and discharged in an efficient manner.  A proper case-study of the preparation, planning, mitigation, and response efforts during the Fall of 2009 is that of the Children's Hospital of Philadelphia (CHOP).  For example, CHOP took several steps to increase the emergency department (ED) surge capacity response abilities through careful planning and mitigation efforts.  To increase ED capacity and response, CHOP used portions of the main lobby area as an ED waiting room; several of the region's hospital-based outpatient facilities were in use during evening and weekend hours for non-emergent cases; the ED's 24-hour short-stay unit was utilized to care for ED patients in a longer-term capacity; non-board certified physicians (in pediatric emergency medicine) and inpatient-unit medical nurses were utilized for ED patient care; hospital units normally utilized for other medical or therapeutic purposes were transformed into ED patient rooms; and rooms normally used for only one patient were expanded to at least a capacity of 2<ref>{{cite journal|last=Scarfone|first=Dr. Richard J.|coauthors=Dr. Susan Coffin, Dr. Evan S. Fieldston, Grace Falkowski, Mary G. Cooney, and Stephanie Grenfell|title=Hospital-Based Pandemic Influenza Preparedness and Response: Strategies to Increase Surge Capacity|journal=Pediatric Emergency Care|year=2011|month=June|volume=27|issue=6|pages=565–572|doi=10.1097/PEC.0b013e31821dc9d1|pmid=21642799}}</ref>

==Comparisons to other pandemics and epidemics==
Annual influenza epidemics are estimated to affect 5–15% of the global population. Although most cases are mild, these epidemics still cause severe illness in {{Nowrap|3–5 million}} people and 250,000–500,000 deaths worldwide.<ref name="WHO Influenza"/> On average 41,400 people die of influenza-related illnesses each year in the United States, based on data collected between 1979 and 2001.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://aje.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/full/163/2/181 |title=Mortality due to Influenza in the United States – An Annualized Regression Approach Using Multiple-Cause Mortality Data | first1 = J.| last1 = Dushoff | first2 = J. B.| last2 = Plotkin| first3 = C.|last3 = Viboud| first4 = D. J. D. |last4 = Earn | first5 = L. | last5 = Simonsen| journal=[[American Journal of Epidemiology]]| volume = 163| issue = 2| pages = 181–7| year = 2006|accessdate=29 October 2009 |quote=The regression model attributes an annual average of 41,400 (95% confidence interval: 27,100, 55,700) deaths to influenza over the period 1979–2001. |doi=10.1093/aje/kwj024 | pmid=16319291| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20091121034700/http://aje.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/full/163/2/181| archivedate= 21 November 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> In industrialised countries, severe illness and deaths occur mainly in the high-risk populations of infants, the elderly and [[chronic illness|chronically ill]] patients,<ref name="WHO Influenza">{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/2003/fs211/en/ |title=Influenza: Fact sheet |date = March 2003|publisher=[[World Health Organization]] (WHO) |accessdate=7 May 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090505070146/http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/2003/fs211/en/| archivedate= 5 May 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> although the H1N1 flu outbreak (like the 1918 [[Spanish flu]]) differs in its tendency to affect younger, healthier people.<ref name="Swine flu affect the young">{{cite web|url=http://bulletin.aarp.org/yourhealth/diseases/articles/swine_flus_tendency_to_strike_the_young_is_causing_confusion.html |title=Swine flu's tendency to strike the young is causing confusion |date=18 September 2009|work=Los Angeles Times |first=Karen |last=Kaplan |accessdate=18 September 2009| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090919215923/http://bulletin.aarp.org/yourhealth/diseases/articles/swine_flus_tendency_to_strike_the_young_is_causing_confusion.html| archivedate= 19 September 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

In addition to these annual epidemics, Influenza A virus strains caused three global pandemics during the 20th century: the Spanish flu in 1918, [[Asian Flu|Asian flu]] in 1957, and [[Hong Kong flu]] in 1968–69. These virus strains had undergone [[antigenic shift|major genetic changes]] for which the population did not possess significant [[immunity (medical)|immunity]].<ref name="EID_Pandemics">{{Cite journal|last=Kilbourne |first=ED |date = January 2006|title=Influenza pandemics of the 20th century |journal=[[Emerging Infectious Diseases]] |volume=12 |issue=1 |url=http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/EID/vol12no01/05-1254.htm|accessdate=26 September 2009|publisher=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |last2=Zhang |first2=Yan B. |last3=Lin |first3=Mei-Chen |pmid=16494710|pages=9–14|doi=10.3201/eid1201.051254| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20090925215450/http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/EID/vol12no01/05-1254.htm| archivedate= 25 September 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= yes}}</ref> Recent genetic analysis has revealed that three-quarters, or six out of the eight genetic segments, of the 2009 flu pandemic strain arose from the North American swine flu strains circulating since 1998, when a new strain was first identified on a factory farm in North Carolina, and which was the first-ever reported triple-hybrid flu virus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hsus.org/farm/news/ournews/swine_flu_virus_origin_1998_042909.html|title=CDC Confirms Ties to Virus First Discovered in U.S. Pig Factories|last=Greger|first=Dr. Michael|date=26 August 2009|publisher=The Humane Society of the United States|accessdate=21 September 2009|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5k5hTrO4Y|archivedate=26 September 2009|deadurl=no}}</ref>

The [[1918 flu epidemic]] began with a wave of mild cases in the spring, followed by more deadly waves in the autumn, eventually killing hundreds of thousands in the United States.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/health/2009-05-26-swine-flu-decrease_N.htm |title=CDC expert says flu outbreak is dying down – for now |last=Sternberg|first=Steve |date=26 May 2009 |work=USA Today |accessdate=17 September 2009}}</ref> The great majority of deaths in the 1918 flu pandemic were the result of secondary bacterial pneumonia. The influenza virus damaged the lining of the [[bronchial tube]]s and lungs of victims, allowing common bacteria from the nose and throat to infect their lungs. Subsequent pandemics have had many fewer fatalities due to the development of antibiotic medicines which can treat pneumonia.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/full/10.1086/591708 |title=Predominant Role of Bacterial Pneumonia as a Cause of Death in Pandemic Influenza: Implications for Pandemic Influenza Preparedness|author=David M. Morens, Jeffery K. Taubenberger, and Anthony S. Fauci|volume=198|issue=7|pages=962–970|journal=[[The Journal of Infectious Diseases]] |accessdate=1 November 2009 |date=1 October 2008|doi=10.1086/591708|pmc=2599911 |pmid=18710327}}</ref>

