The influenza virus has also caused several pandemic threats over the past century, including the pseudo-pandemic of 1947 (thought of as mild because although globally distributed, it caused relatively few deaths),<ref name="EID_Pandemics" /> the [[1976 swine flu outbreak]] and the [[Influenza A virus subtype H1N1#Russian flu|1977 Russian flu]], all caused by the H1N1 subtype.<ref name="EID_Pandemics"/> The world has been at an increased level of alert since the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS]] epidemic in Southeast Asia (caused by the [[SARS coronavirus]]).<ref>{{Cite news|date= 29 April 2009 |first=David |last=Brown |title=System set up after SARS epidemic was slow to alert global authorities |work=The Washington Post |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/04/29/AR2009042904911.html|accessdate=26 September 2009}}</ref> The level of preparedness was further increased and sustained with the advent of the [[Influenza A virus subtype H5N1|H5N1 bird flu]] outbreaks because of H5N1's high fatality rate, although the strains currently prevalent have limited human-to-human transmission ([[anthroponotic]]) capability, or epidemicity.<ref>{{Cite journal|author=Beigel JH, Farrar J, Han AM, Hayden FG, Hyer R, de Jong MD, Lochindarat S, Nguyen TK, Nguyen TH, Tran TH, Nicoll A, Touch S, Yuen KY; Writing Committee of the World Health Organization (WHO) Consultation on Human Influenza A/H5 |title=Avian influenza A (H5N1) infection in humans |journal=[[The New England Journal of Medicine]] |volume=353 |issue=13 |pages=1374–85 |date=29 September 2005|pmid=16192482 |doi=10.1056/NEJMra052211 |url=http://content.nejm.org/cgi/content/full/353/13/1374| accessdate= 14 April 2011 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>

People who contracted flu before 1957 appeared to have some immunity to H1N1 flu. Dr. Daniel Jernigan, head of flu epidemiology for the U.S. CDC, has stated: "Tests on [[blood serum]] from older people showed that they had [[antibodies]] that attacked the new virus&nbsp;... That does not mean that everyone over 52 is immune, since Americans and Mexicans older than that have died of the new flu".<ref name="Don McNeil, 20 May">{{Cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/21/health/21swineflu.html |title=U.S. Says Older People Appear Safer From New Flu Strain |work=The New York Times |last=McNeil Jr. |first=Donald G. |date=20 May 2009|accessdate=26 September 2009}}</ref>

